{"type":"text","timestamp":1778610364527,"sessionID":"ses_1e292bc26ffewTlHueTbf6ZKk8","part":{"id":"prt_e1d705d2e001WCSV4o0ppmavCh","messageID":"msg_e1d6dbe62001JMJVBShjrDZuiK","sessionID":"ses_1e292bc26ffewTlHueTbf6ZKk8","type":"text","text":"The strongest low-risk micro-opt I found is not another predictor or bypass: split the 64-bit RVFI order incrementer in `core.sv`. It preserves IPC and RVFI semantics while potentially removing a 64-bit carry chain from the synthesized FPGA timing graph.","time":{"start":1778610363694,"end":1778610364526},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0c0dcaa2701a1220016a0370bb8a1481909ad0240895987dab","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778610380308,"sessionID":"ses_1e292bc26ffewTlHueTbf6ZKk8","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_W8nSPLViUp8BkW0RHKgnmqpb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r10s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Split RVFI order counter\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent successful bench changes improved fitness by trimming timing and routing\n+  pressure without adding frontend prediction, memory bypasses, or new pipeline\n+  state. The top-level RVFI order counter still increments a full 64-bit value on\n+  every retirement, and that counter is synthesized into the FPGA build even\n+  though CoreMark only needs monotonic retirement numbering for checking.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the single 64-bit rvfi_order_q + 1 incrementer in rtl/core.sv with a\n+  split low/high counter: increment a 32-bit low half every valid retirement and\n+  increment the high half only when the low half wraps. Drive the RVFI order port\n+  from the concatenated halves, preserving reset-to-zero and strict +1 monotonic\n+  ordering across all retirements.\n+\n+  This keeps the NRET=1 port contract, retirement boundary, IPC, trap behavior,\n+  and all memory behavior unchanged. If the current FPGA timing graph includes\n+  the 64-bit RVFI carry chain or its routing fanout, shortening it to two smaller\n+  counters should modestly raise median Fmax with essentially no CoreMark cycle\n+  cost. If the order counter is not timing-relevant, the change should be nearly\n+  neutral.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Split the RVFI order state into low/high halves and preserve the same concatenated order value on the channel-0 RVFI port.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r10s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r10s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r10s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r10s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r10s0\n+title: \"Split RVFI order counter\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent successful bench changes improved fitness by trimming timing and routing\n+  pressure without adding frontend prediction, memory bypasses, or new pipeline\n+  state. The top-level RVFI order counter still increments a full 64-bit value on\n+  every retirement, and that counter is synthesized into the FPGA build even\n+  though CoreMark only needs monotonic retirement numbering for checking.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the single 64-bit rvfi_order_q + 1 incrementer in rtl/core.sv with a\n+  split low/high counter: increment a 32-bit low half every valid retirement and\n+  increment the high half only when the low half wraps. Drive the RVFI order port\n+  from the concatenated halves, preserving reset-to-zero and strict +1 monotonic\n+  ordering across all retirements.\n+\n+  This keeps the NRET=1 port contract, retirement boundary, IPC, trap behavior,\n+  and all memory behavior unchanged. If the current FPGA timing graph includes\n+  the 64-bit RVFI carry chain or its routing fanout, shortening it to two smaller\n+  counters should modestly raise median Fmax with essentially no CoreMark cycle\n+  cost. If the order counter is not timing-relevant, the change should be nearly\n+  neutral.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/cor