{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778612567502,"sessionID":"ses_1e26f75b3ffeVj9RbJ4kTWRht5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_5sfLH3ZQ6JgdoI36XANxpHx7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"title.*replay|replay table|ifetch replay|Resetless IF|Wider","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 5 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Redirect target replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts found real CoreMark loop-control opportunity, but every design that changed the normal fetch next-PC path with predecode, PC compares, target muxes, or prediction metadata lost more Fmax than it recovered in CPI. The remaining predictor angle should avoid making every sequential fetch pay for loop prediction.\\n\\nA tiny target-instruction replay buffer can target the same repeated taken backedges without predicting the PC ahead of time. It only acts on an actual EX redirect and tries to fill the redirect bubble with a previously observed target instruction, so the common pc+4 fetch path stays essentially unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts found real CoreMark loop-control opportunity, but every design that changed the normal fetch next-PC path with predecode, PC compares, target muxes, or prediction metadata lost more Fmax than it recovered in CPI. The remaining predictor angle should avoid making every sequential fetch pay for loop prediction.\\n\\nA tiny target-instruction replay buffer can target the same repeated taken backedges without predicting the PC ahead of time. It only acts on an actual EX redirect and tries to fill the redirect bubble with a previously observed target instruction, so the common pc+4 fetch path stays essentially unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry redirect-target replay predictor inside IF. When a taken branch or jump redirects to a target and the target instruction is fetched normally, record the target PC and instruction word. On a later EX redirect to the same target, emit the cached target instruction and target PC into ID during the redirect cycle instead of forcing a NOP, while still updating the real PC to the redirect target.\\n\\nThis should recover one bubble for hot loop backedges after warmup without a BTB lookup, current-PC tag compare, imem_data ...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped instruction replay predictor trained only by accepted\\ninstruction fetches. On an io_imemReady=1 fetch, record {PC tag, instruction}\\nin an 8-entry table. On a later io_imemReady=0 cycle, if the current PC hits\\nthe table, supply the cached instruction and treat fetch as effectively ready;\\notherwise keep the existing stall/NOP behavior.\\n\\nThis is not a branch target predictor and does not carry prediction metadata\\ninto EX. It attacks repeated hot-loop iStalls while avoiding the failed IF\\nbranch-predecode/BTB/RAS/backedge-repair paths. Because the instruction memory\\nis immutable in FPGA/cosim and formal ties io_imemReady high, a replay hit is\\narchitecturally the same instruction word previously observed for that PC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an 8-entry PC-tagged instruction replay predictor, fill it on accepted ready fetches,...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Resetless IF replay payloads\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the accepted-fetch-only replay behavior exactly as-is, but reset only the\\nreplay_valid bits. Leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload registers\\nresetless because they are architecturally ignored whenever their valid bit is\\nclear and fully overwritten before any replay hit can occur.\\n\\nThis should trim synchronous reset muxing and reset-tree fanout introduced by\\nthe replay predictor without adding new prediction metadata, bypassing, or PC\\nmuxing. IPC should remain unchanged, while median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may rise\\nmodestly from lower IF-stage routing pressure.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Reset only replay_valid and the PC; leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload arrays resetless while preserving fill-on-imem-ready and replay-hit gating.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_de...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Wider resetless ifetch replay cache\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild the IF replay table as a 16-entry direct-mapped, valid-gated replay\\ncache indexed by pc[5:2]. Fill it only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, and\\non io_imemReady=0 hits keep supplying the cached instruction through the\\nexisting imem_effective_ready path. Do not add branch prediction metadata,\\ntarget repair state, or any EX feedback.\\n\\nMake the replay tag and instruction payload arrays reset...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Wider ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only successful predictor result so far was the tiny instruction-fetch\\nreplay table, because it converts random hot-loop instruction-bus stalls into\\nuseful decode cycles without adding branch target lookup, prediction repair,\\nor EX-stage metadata. CoreMark's timed working set is larger than eight\\nfetch-table slots, so direct-mapped conflicts can still turn repeated PCs\\nback into imem stalls even after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only successful predictor result so far was the tiny instruction-fetch\\nreplay table, because it converts random hot-loop instruction-bus stalls into\\nuseful decode cycles without adding branch target lookup, prediction repair,\\nor EX-stage metadata. CoreMark's timed working set is larger than eight\\nfetch-table slots, so direct-mapped conflicts can still turn repeated PCs\\nback into imem stalls even after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the IF-stage instruction replay predictor from 8 direct-mapped entries\\nto 16 direct-mapped entries while keeping the exact same training and use\\ndiscipline: fill only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, replay only when\\nio_imemReady is low and the current PC tag hits, and leave all branch/jump\\nprediction behavior unchanged. This should reduce replay conflict misses in\\nCoreMark hot loops under the 22% random iStall model while avoiding the\\ntarget-PC muxing and prediction-repair metadata that made earlier branch\\npredictors regress. The added hardware is one more index bit and a modestly\\nlarger tag/instruction array, so the expected gain is smaller than the first\\nreplay predictor but still plausible.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Increase the PC-tagged instruction replay predictor to 16 direct-mapped entries, preserving fill-on-ready and replay-on-stall semantics.\"}...","metadata":{"matches":5,"truncated":false},"title":"title.*replay|replay table|ifetch replay|Resetless IF|Wider","time":{"start":1778612567464,"end":1778612567501}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09955188489488a2016a03795751dc8193b13544d028ac0016"}},"id":"prt_e1d91fda60018X6rPXn130gFrQ","sessionID":"ses_1e26f75b3ffeVj9RbJ4kTWRht5","messageID":"msg_e1d912aaa001eZ5KcNdSgIx00L"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778612567503,"sessionID":"ses_1e26f75b3ffeVj9RbJ4kTWRht5","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_UYHHGsKQYVgZ3zXA10vGg29S","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2|hyp-20260512-001-r11s0|hyp-20260512-002-r11s1|hyp-20260512-003-r11s2","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 4 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped instruction replay predictor trained only by accepted\\ninstruction fetches. On an io_imemReady=1 fetch, record {PC tag, instruction}\\nin an 8-entry table. On a later io_imemReady=0 cycle, if the current PC hits\\nthe table, supply the cached instruction and treat fetch as effectively ready;\\notherwise keep the existing stall/NOP behavior.\\n\\nThis is not a branch target predictor and does not carry prediction metadata\\ninto EX. It attacks repeated hot-loop iStalls while avoiding the failed IF\\nbranch-predecode/BTB/RAS/backedge-repair paths. Because the instruction memory\\nis immutable in FPGA/cosim and formal ties io_imemReady high, a replay hit is\\narchitecturally the same instruction word previously observed for that PC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an 8-entry PC-tagged instruction replay predictor, fill it on accepted ready fetches,...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Resetless IF replay payloads\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the accepted-fetch-only replay behavior exactly as-is, but reset only the\\nreplay_valid bits. Leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload registers\\nresetless because they are architecturally ignored whenever their valid bit is\\nclear and fully overwritten before any replay hit can occur.\\n\\nThis should trim synchronous reset muxing and reset-tree fanout introduced by\\nthe replay predictor without adding new prediction metadata, bypassing, or PC\\nmuxing. IPC should remain unchanged, while median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may rise\\nmodestly from lower IF-stage routing pressure.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Reset only replay_valid and the PC; leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload arrays resetless while preserving fill-on-imem-ready and replay-hit gating.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_de...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Wider resetless ifetch replay cache\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild the IF replay table as a 16-entry direct-mapped, valid-gated replay\\ncache indexed by pc[5:2]. Fill it only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, and\\non io_imemReady=0 hits keep supplying the cached instruction through the\\nexisting imem_effective_ready path. Do not add branch prediction metadata,\\ntarget repair state, or any EX feedback.\\n\\nMake the replay tag and instruction payload arrays reset...\n  Line 34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Wider ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only successful predictor result so far was the tiny instruction-fetch\\nreplay table, because it converts random hot-loop instruction-bus stalls into\\nuseful decode cycles without adding branch target lookup, prediction repair,\\nor EX-stage metadata. CoreMark's timed working set is larger than eight\\nfetch-table slots, so direct-mapped conflicts can still turn repeated PCs\\nback into imem stalls even after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only successful predictor result so far was the tiny instruction-fetch\\nreplay table, because it converts random hot-loop instruction-bus stalls into\\nuseful decode cycles without adding branch target lookup, prediction repair,\\nor EX-stage metadata. CoreMark's timed working set is larger than eight\\nfetch-table slots, so direct-mapped conflicts can still turn repeated PCs\\nback into imem stalls even after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the IF-stage instruction replay predictor from 8 direct-mapped entries\\nto 16 direct-mapped entries while keeping the exact same training and use\\ndiscipline: fill only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, replay only when\\nio_imemReady is low and the current PC tag hits, and leave all branch/jump\\nprediction behavior unchanged. This should reduce replay conflict misses in\\nCoreMark hot loops under the 22% random iStall model while avoiding the\\ntarget-PC muxing and prediction-repair metadata that made earlier branch\\npredictors regress. The added hardware is one more index bit and a modestly\\nlarger tag/instruction array, so the expected gain is smaller than the first\\nreplay predictor but still plausible.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Increase the PC-tagged instruction replay predictor to 16 direct-mapped entries, preserving fill-on-ready and replay-on-stall semantics.\"}...","metadata":{"matches":4,"truncated":false},"title":"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2|hyp-20260512-001-r11s0|hyp-20260512-002-r11s1|hyp-20260512-003-r11s2","time":{"start":1778612567461,"end":1778612567502}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09955188489488a2016a03795751cc8193b8fc7f93ce369d33"}},"id":"prt_e1d91fda1001AP2WBPmtGEtXS6","sessionID":"ses_1e26f75b3ffeVj9RbJ4kTWRht5","messageID":"msg_e1d912aaa001eZ5KcNdSgIx00L"}}
