:\n24:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n25:   confidence: medium\n26: changes:\n27:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n28:     description: \"Store and compare only replay_tag=pc[19:5] while preserving the 8-entry pc[4:2] index, fill-on-ready behavior, replay-on-stall hit semantics, and NRET=1 top-level contract.\"\n\n(End of file - total 28 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\ntitle: \"Trim IF replay tags to memory range\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The 8-entry IF replay table is the current strongest cycle-side win, but the\n  follow-up attempts show the table is sensitive to routing: resetless payloads\n  and wider tables regressed, and the lesson points at compare/control cost\n  rather than capacity. Each replay entry still stores and compares pc[31:5],\n  even though valid instruction fetches for this benchmark contract are bounded\n  to the 1 MiB memory window.\nhypothesis: |\n  Keep the accepted-fetch-only 8-entry replay table and its exact ready/hit\n  semantics, but shrink replay_tag from pc[31:5] to pc[19:5]. Together with the\n  existing pc[4:2] index, those bits uniquely identify every word-aligned fetch\n  address in the legal [0x00000000, 0x00100000) instruction-memory region, so\n  CoreMark hit behavior and correctness for in-bounds execution are unchanged.\n\n  This removes 96 replay-tag flops and cuts each replay-hit comparator from 27\n  bits to 15 bits, directly attacking the IF-stage compare/routing pressure that\n  likely limited the replay-table follow-ups. Formal keeps imemReady high, and","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r12s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778612924734,"end":1778612924739}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05a3410bf54763da016a037abc9d14819397df36c09ff13bf1"}},"id":"prt_e1d97713600102GDeLCCdQ4PF5","sessionID":"ses_1e26f75b3ffeVj9RbJ4kTWRht5","messageID":"msg_e1d9716700013ZKEk0dhxFlZ11"}}
