{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778615793160,"sessionID":"ses_1e23d079bffeuSJQ2dbzbV0CwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_rk87CM6MaF9nwG3Gx00MqjGe","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (improvement, +41.63%): Moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU mux into an iterative ex_stage div_unit removes rare divide hardware from the FPGA critical path while CoreMark's divide-sparse mix hides the stall latency.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Multi-cycle M-units need a done/ack guard that prevents a held ID/EX M instruction from reasserting start on the ready cycle, or RV32M retirement can lose/corrupt the result in cosim.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +5.13%): IF-stage static branch/JAL predecode can lengthen the imem_data-to-next_pc fetch critical path enough that Fmax loss outweighs CoreMark loop-back bubble savings.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -4.44%): Sharing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU through one sign-controlled 33x33 product can hurt Fmax because operand-signedness muxing and the wider 66-bit multiply cone outweigh removing parallel 32x32 product nets.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -21.07%): A two-entry IF skid queue can cost more than it hides in this shallow CoreMark pipeline, as fetch_pc/valid/pop/full muxing outweighed limited overlap between random imem stalls and backend stalls.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -43.44%): A PC-indexed BTB still puts tag/counter/target lookup plus predicted-next-PC plumbing on the fetch/control path, and in this shallow CoreMark pipeline that cost can swamp warmed-up loop prediction wins.\n7: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (regression, -11.99%): Operand-sensitive load-use predecode plus a MEM-stage store-data bypass can cost more Fmax/control complexity than it saves when CoreMark has too few load-to-store rs2-only bubbles to amortize the extra muxing.\n8: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.50%): A one-entry RAM store buffer still adds sbuf_valid/dmem_ready muxing and ordered-memory stall control on the MEM/hazard path, and CoreMark's random store backpressure was not dominant enough to amortize that backend complexity.\n9: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -38.25%): Even a single-entry tagged redirect predictor leaves a PC tag compare, target mux, and predicted-next-PC metadata on the shallow fetch/EX control path, so shrinking the BTB table alone does not recover enough CoreMark loop bubbles to pay for prediction.\n10: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -4.14%): Moving only MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an iterative ex_stage unit can regress because low-half MUL still keeps the main multiplier cone while added busy/done/result muxing lands on the common EX timing path.\n11: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -49.57%): Return-only RAS prediction still adds imem_data return decode, stack-top next_pc muxing, and predicted-next-PC repair plumbing to the shallow fetch/EX control path, while CoreMark call/return traffic was too sparse to amortize the timing cost.\n12: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.43%): Replacing MEM-stage variable byte-lane shifts with explicit case selectors can regress because synthesis already handles the tiny addr[1:0] shift well, while duplicated load/store mask trees add mux/control pressure on the common load-data and RVFI mask cones.\n13: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -12.44%): Pipelining all MUL variants out of alu.sv into mul_unit still regressed because ex_stage busy/done/result and operand-preservation muxing plus CoreMark MUL stall cycles outweighed removing the product cone from the common ALU path.\n14: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -16.83%): Even a tagless pc[7:2] conditional-backedge predictor leaves a fetch PC compare/target mux plus predicted-next-PC repair plumbing, so CoreMark loop prediction needs a path that avoids adding IF critical-path work.\n15: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (improvement, +6.74%): Stage-specific pipeline control structs improved fitness by dropping EX-only LUI/branch metadata before MEM/WB, showing this shallow FPGA core is fanout/routing-limited enough that pruning dead flops can beat adding control.\n16: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -0.14%): Making the 2R1W write-first register file resetless did not move fitness, suggesting its async read/bypass muxing rather than reset clearing is the relevant FPGA timing/area cost.\n17: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -9.81%): A tagless countdown loop predictor still regressed because counter-zero target muxing plus pred_next_pc metadata and EX-wide prediction_miss repair stayed on common fetch/control paths, outweighing CoreMark backedge bubble savings.\n18: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (improvement, +1.09%): Resetting only valid/control/hazard fields in pipeline registers trims synchronous reset muxing on wide payload flops, confirming PC/instr/RVFI data can stay don't-care while invalid when side effects are valid-gated.\n19: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (broken, n/a): MEM/WB forwarding cannot be gated by valid-or-current-hold alone because dmem-stall release still needs the invalid-but-held load payload/control for the dependent EX instruction, so resetless payload cleanup must preserve that bypass contract.\n20: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -18.42%): Decode-stage direct-JAL prediction still adds decoder/imm_gen/target-add feedback into the IF PC mux, and CoreMark's direct-JAL bubble savings were too small to offset that new control-path timing cost.\n21: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r8s0 (regression, -3.83%): Removing duplicate EX/MEM store-data payload can regress when the extra register was isolating rs2_val fanout between MEM byte-replication/store paths and RVFI source reporting.\n22: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r8s1 (regression, -10.76%): Same-cycle MEM-to-EX load bypass puts dmem read-data extension and ready/forward gating on the EX operand/redirect path, so its timing cost can outweigh CoreMark load-use bubble savings.\n23: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r8s2 (regression, -22.31%): Registering a one-entry backedge predictor avoids same-cycle tag lookup but still adds pred_valid/target PC muxing plus EX miss/clear/train plumbing, so predictor repair metadata alone can outweigh CoreMark loop-bubble savings.\n24: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r9s0 (regression, -4.46%): Explicitly sharing EX pc_plus4/pc_imm_sum/JALR target and branch comparator primitives can regress because synthesis already optimizes these simple cones, while the named shared nets increase fanout across redirect, link, pc_next, and RVFI paths.\n25: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r9s1 (regression, -10.21%): Registering a single MEM/WB wb_data value can regress because it moves the load-vs-ALU mux onto the MEM/load-data capture path while removing a late WB mux that synthesis already handled cheaply.\n26: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r9s2 (regression, -22.23%): Redirect-target instruction replay avoided normal pc+4 prediction work but still regressed because replay-hit compares, target+4 PC muxing, and flush suppression moved complexity onto the redirect/hazard path where CoreMark bubble savings could not amortize it.\n27: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r10s0 (regression, +4.63%): Splitting rvfi_order into lo/hi counters can regress because FPGA synthesis already maps a 64-bit incrementer efficiently, while the explicit low-wrap compare and high-half enable add control/routing overhead on retirement logic.\n28: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r10s1 (regression, -26.19%): Removing regfile write-first muxes by adding a captured previous-WB forwarding source can regress because the extra EX operand select path and ID/EX-held bypass state cost more than the rare same-cycle WB/read repair they replace.\n29: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r10s2 (improvement, +21.48%): An IF replay table trained only on accepted fetches can turn CoreMark's random hot-loop imem stalls into useful instructions via imem_effective_ready without paying the target-lookup and EX-repair metadata costs that sank branch predictors.\n30: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r11s0 (regression, -8.82%): Making IF replay tag/instr payload arrays resetless regressed despite valid gating, so the replay table's binding cost is likely compare/control routing rather than reset mux fanout on its small payload flops.\n31: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r11s1 (regression, -5.04%): Widening the direct-mapped IF replay table from 8 to 16 entries regressed, suggesting CoreMark replay is not capacity-limited enough to pay for extra index/tag/valid routing on the fetch path.\n32: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r12s0 (regression, +0.00%): Shrinking IF replay tags from pc[31:5] to pc[19:5] did not move fitness, implying the accepted-fetch replay table is limited by ready/hit control and fetch mux routing rather than raw tag flop/comparator width.\n33: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r12s1 (regression, -57.52%): Opportunistic IF replay warming during backend stalls regressed because decoupling io_imemAddr from pc adds imem_addr_q==pc qualification, warm-cursor updates, and replay-fill muxing on the fetch ready/hit path that extra training could not amortize.\n34: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r12s2 (regression, -19.56%): Line-packed IF replay regressed because half-select valid/data muxing and wider line-tag update control add fetch-ready path complexity that outweighed reducing the number of stored tags.\n35: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r13s0 (broken, n/a): Suppressing false load-use stalls still must preserve RVFI raw rs1/rs2 register contents for aliased unused fields, or younger instructions can retire stale source data that riscv-formal's reg check catches.\n36: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r13s1 (regression, -31.01%): A real IF/ID register can cost more than it saves in this shallow CoreMark core when its valid/hold/flush handoff adds redirect bubbles and control muxing around the existing accepted-fetch replay path.\n37: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r13s2 (regression, -18.43%): Filtering IF replay training with flush/redirect hurt, so wrong-path fall-through fills are less costly than adding redirect-qualified replay-write control and losing the table's simple imem_ready-only behavior.\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (improvement, +41.63%): Moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU mux into an iterative ex_stage div_unit removes rare divide hardware from the FPGA critical path while CoreMark's divide-sparse mix hides the stall latency.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Multi-cycle M-units need a done/ack guard that prevents a held ID/EX M instruction from reasserting start on the ready cycle, or RV32M retirement can lose/corrupt the result in cosim.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +5.13%): IF-stage static branch/JAL predecode can lengthen the imem_data-to-next_pc fetch critical path enough that Fmax loss outweighs CoreMark loop-back bubble savings.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -4.44%): Sharing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU through one sign-controlled 33x33 product can hurt Fmax because operand-signedness muxing and the wider 66-bit multiply cone outweigh removing parallel 32x32 product nets.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -21.07%): A two-entry IF skid queue can cost more than it hides in this shallow CoreMark pipeline, as fetch_pc/valid/pop/full muxing outweighed limited overlap between random imem stalls and backend stalls.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -43.44%): A PC-indexed BTB still puts tag/counter/target lookup plus predicted-next-PC plumbing on the fetch/control path, and in this shallow CoreMark pipeline that cost can swamp warmed-up loop prediction wins.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (regression, -11.99%): Operand-sensitive load-use predecode plus a MEM-stage store-data bypass can cost more Fmax/control complexity than it saves when CoreMark has too few load-to-store rs2-only bubbles to amortize the extra muxing.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.50%): A one-entry RAM store buffer still adds sbuf_valid/dmem_ready muxing and ordered-memory stall control on the MEM/hazard path, and CoreMark's random store backpressure was not dominant enough to amortize that backend complexity.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -38.25%): Even a single-entry tagged redirect predictor leaves a PC tag compare, target mux, and predicted-next-PC metadata on the shallow fetch/EX control path, so shrinking the BTB table alone does not recover enough CoreMark loop bubbles to pay for prediction.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -4.14%): Moving only MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an iterative ex_stage unit can regress because low-half MUL still keeps the main multiplier cone while added busy/done/result muxing lands on the common EX timing path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -49.57%): Return-only RAS prediction still adds imem_data return decode, stack-top next_pc muxing, and predicted-next-PC repair plumbing to the shallow fetch/EX control path, while CoreMark call/return traffic was too sparse to amortize the timing cost.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.43%): Replacing MEM-stage variable byte-lane shifts with explicit case selectors can regress because synthesis already handles the tiny addr[1:0] shift well, while duplicated load/store mask trees add mux/control pressure on the common load-data and RVFI mask cones.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -12.44%): Pipelining all MUL variants out of alu.sv into mul_unit still regressed because ex_stage busy/done/result and operand-preservation muxing plus CoreMark MUL stall cycles outweighed removing the product cone from the common ALU path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -16.83%): Even a tagless pc[7:2] conditional-backedge predictor leaves a fetch PC compare/target mux plus predicted-next-PC repair plumbing, so CoreMark loop prediction needs a path that avoids adding IF critical-path work.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (improvement, +6.74%): Stage-specific pipeline control structs improved fitness by dropping EX-only LUI/branch metadata before MEM/WB, showing this shallow FPGA core is fanout/routing-limited enough that pruning dead flops can beat adding control.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -0.14%): Making the 2R1W write-first register file resetless did not move fitness, suggesting its async read/bypass muxing rather than reset clearing is the relevant FPGA timing/area cost.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -9.81%): A tagless countdown loop predictor still regressed because counter-zero target muxing plus pred_next_pc metadata and EX-wide prediction_miss repair stayed on common fetch/control paths, outweighing CoreMark backedge bubble savings.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (improvement, +1.09%): Resetting only valid/control/hazard fields in pipeline registers trims synchronous reset muxing on wide payload flops, confirming PC/instr/RVFI data can stay don't-care while invalid when side effects are valid-gated.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (broken, n/a): MEM/WB forwarding cannot be gated by valid-or-current-hold alone because dmem-stall release still needs the invalid-but-held load payload/control for the dependent EX instruction, so resetless payload cleanup must preserve that bypass contract.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -18.42%): Decode-stage direct-JAL prediction still adds decoder/imm_gen/target-add feedback into the IF PC mux, and CoreMark's direct-JAL bubble savings were too small to offset that new control-path timing cost.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778615793152,"end":1778615793159}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c60b39e293c9d6c016a0385f101488194904d90441d7ff207"}},"id":"prt_e1dc335d7001xljbwiUmKSHoj1","sessionID":"ses_1e23d079bffeuSJQ2dbzbV0CwL","messageID":"msg_e1dc2f8b7001RvtETq9ICkp8W4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778615793165,"sessionID":"ses_1e23d079bffeuSJQ2dbzbV0CwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_6J6pTRQgTytDudqj9tXT9OhR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category: micro_opt|\"category\": \"micro_opt\"|micro_opt|hyp-20260512-003-r10s2|hyp-20260512-001-r6s0|hyp-20260512-001-r7s0","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 15 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4c67411\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-12T14:04:33.574191Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative divider off ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with a small iterative divider/rem unit and\\nstall the single-issue pipeline while that unit is busy. Keep ADD/SUB/logic,\\nshifts, compares, address generation, branches, jumps, and all MUL/MULH\\nvariants single-cycle. This trades latency on rare divide instructions for a\\nshorter EX-stage combinational path and lower LUT pressure, which should raise\\nmedian Tang Nano 20K Fmax without materially changing CoreMark cycles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real combinational DIV/REM/% paths from the ALU while preserving ALTOPS behavior and single-cycle non-divide operations.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a sequential RV32M-correct divider/remainder unit covering signed, unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Start the divider for DIV/REM ops, hold the instruction until completion, and latch the final quotient or remainder into EX/MEM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an execute-busy stall input so IF...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Share RV32M multiplier datapath\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU, the remaining RV32M\\nmultiplier logic is a likely Fmax and routing limiter. The current ALU\\ncomputes signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned 64-bit\\nproducts in parallel even though each instruction consumes only one result.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU, the remaining RV32M\\nmultiplier logic is a likely Fmax and routing limiter. The current ALU\\ncomputes signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned 64-bit\\nproducts in parallel even though each instruction consumes only one result.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three parallel product nets with a single sign-controlled\\nextended multiply selected from the ALU_MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU operation.\\nMUL can still use the low 32 bits, while the high-half variants select the\\ncorrect signedness through operand extension. This should reduce LUT/DSP\\nduplication and the ALU result-mux/routing cone without changing pipeline\\nlatency, CoreMark instruction count, RVFI behavior, or ALTOPS semantics.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Collapse the three RV32M multiply products into one sign-selected extended product while preserving ALTOPS substitutions and single-cycle MUL latency.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Keep or extend MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors to guard signedness correctness after sharing the multiplier datapath.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Collapse the three RV32M multiply products into one sign-selected extended product while preserving ALTOPS substitutions and single-cycle MUL latency.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Keep or extend MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Late load-store data bypass\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector stalls whenever a load in EX has an rd\\nmatching either raw source field of the following IF/ID instruction. That is\\nnecessary for ALU operands, branch compares, and store address bases, but it\\nis over-conservative for a STORE whose rs2 data is not consumed until MEM.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels perform many load/store moves and immediate-form\\noperations, so avoidable one-cycle bubbles directly reduce iterations per\\ncycle without helping correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector stalls whenever a load in EX has an rd\\nmatching either raw source field of the following IF/ID instruction. That is\\nnecessary for ALU operands, branch compares, and store address bases, but it\\nis over-conservative for a STORE whose rs2 data is not consumed until MEM.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels perform many load/store moves and immediate-form\\noperations, so avoidable one-cycle bubbles directly reduce iterations per\\ncycle without helping correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refine the load-use hazard to distinguish operands needed in EX from store\\ndata that can be supplied one stage later. For a following STORE, keep the\\nstall only when the load feeds rs1, the address base; allow an rs2-only\\ndependency to advance and resolve it with a MEM-stage bypass from the current\\nMEM/WB result into the store-data path. The bypass must also update the\\nretiring store's RVFI rs2_rdata and mem_wdata fields so formal/cosim observe\\nthe architectural source value.\\n\\nDefault unknown or illegal encodings to conservative source use in the\\nhazard predecode, preserving trap and RVFI behavior. This should recover IPC\\nfrom load-to-store and false rs2-immediate hazards while adding only a small\\nMEM data mux, avoiding the fetch critical-path costs seen in prior predictor\\nattempts and the EX multiplier regressions from prior micro-opts....\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative high-half multiply\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The successful divider change showed that removing rare RV32M operations from\\nthe common EX-stage combinational cone can raise FPGA Fmax without materially\\nhurting CoreMark cycles. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply\\nproducts in parallel for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU, even though CoreMark's\\ntimed hot path is expected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than\\nhigh-half multiply variants.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The successful divider change showed that removing rare RV32M operations from\\nthe common EX-stage combinational cone can raise FPGA Fmax without materially\\nhurting CoreMark cycles. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply\\nproducts in parallel for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU, even though CoreMark's\\ntimed hot path is expected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than\\nhigh-half multiply variants.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a single-cycle low-half multiply, but move MULH, MULHU, and\\nMULHSU onto a small iterative high-half multiplier that reuses the existing\\nexecute-busy stall pattern. This should let synthesis reduce the common ALU\\nmultiplier to only the low 32 result bits for MUL, while removing the signed\\nand signed/unsigned high-product cones from the normal ADD/branch/load/store\\nexecute path.\\n\\nUnlike the prior shared 33x33 multiplier attempt, this does not add a wider\\nsignedness mux to every multiply operation. The latency penalty is paid only\\nfor high-half M-extension instructions, which should be rare or absent in the\\nCoreMark timed region, while RV32M correctness remains covered by dedicated\\nunit tests and cosim.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real MULH/MULHU/MULHSU product generation from the common ALU path while preserving ALTOPS substitutions and single-cycle ...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Case-decoded load byte lanes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest prior result came from shortening a real timing cone without\\nadding new frontend or memory-ordering state. Recent predictor, store-buffer,\\nand multiplier refinements all regressed because extra muxing and control\\npressure outweighed any cycle savings. The MEM stage still contains dynamic\\nbyte-lane shifts on the load/store path, including a variable right shift by\\naddr[1:0] * 8, which can synthesize into a wider mux cone on the BRAM-read to\\nMEM/WB path used heavily by CoreMark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest prior result came from shortening a real timing cone without\\nadding new frontend or memory-ordering state. Recent predictor, store-buffer,\\nand multiplier refinements all regressed because extra muxing and control\\npressure outweighed any cycle savings. The MEM stage still contains dynamic\\nbyte-lane shifts on the load/store path, including a variable right shift by\\naddr[1:0] * 8, which can synthesize into a wider mux cone on the BRAM-read to\\nMEM/WB path used heavily by CoreMark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte/halfword load extraction and byte-mask generation\\nas explicit small case trees on alu_result[1:0] and mem_width. This removes\\nthe variable shift and shift-amount multiply from the common load path while\\npreserving the existing dmem port contract, misalignment trap gating, RVFI\\nALIGNED_MEM reporting, and single-cycle MEM latency. IPC should be unchanged,\\nbut LUT depth and routing on the load-data and store-mask cones should drop\\nenough to modestly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace dynamic byte-lane shifts and masks with explicit case-based byte/halfword selectors while preserving misalignment, dmem, and RVFI behavior.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Prune dead pipeline control bits\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent bench attempts regressed when they added new muxing or control to the\\nalready-shallow pipeline. The current RTL still carries several EX-only or\\nunused control/state fields through later pipeline registers, including the\\nredundant LUI control bit and unused branch metadata after EX has already\\nresolved the redirect. Those flops and nets do not improve IPC, but they can\\nadd routing pressure and fanout on the FPGA implementation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent bench attempts regressed when they added new muxing or control to the\\nalready-shallow pipeline. The current RTL still carries several EX-only or\\nunused control/state fields through later pipeline registers, including the\\nredundant LUI control bit and unused branch metadata after EX has already\\nresolved the redirect. Those flops and nets do not improve IPC, but they can\\nadd routing pressure and fanout on the FPGA implementation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Narrow the control/state carried past each stage to only what the next stages\\nactually consume. Remove the unused is_lui control bit because LUI is already\\nrepresented by ALU_LUI plus alu_src, stop storing branch_taken/branch_target\\nin EX/MEM after redirect resolution, and explicitly avoid propagating EX-only\\ndecode controls into MEM/WB. This should reduce register count, fanout, and\\nlate-stage routing without changing retirement timing, RVFI contents, trap\\nbehavior, memory ordering, or CoreMark cycle count.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove unused pipeline-bundle fields and narrow late-stage control state to the bits consumed after EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/decoder.sv\", \"description\": \"Drop the redundant is_lui output while preserving ALU_LUI decode and illegal-instruction defaults.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\"...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Valid-only pipeline payload resets\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning bench change improved fitness by pruning dead pipeline\\ncontrol state, which suggests this shallow FPGA core is sensitive to fanout,\\nrouting, and unnecessary flop-side muxing. The stage registers still\\nsynchronously clear wide PC, instruction, operand, immediate, memory, and RVFI\\npayload fields on reset even though retirement and architectural side effects\\nare controlled by valid and compact control bits.\\n\\nThose reset muxes do not improve CoreMark IPC, but they can add high-fanout\\nreset routing and extra logic on the same pipeline registers used by the hot\\nexecute, memory, forwarding, and writeback paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning bench change improved fitness by pruning dead pipeline\\ncontrol state, which suggests this shallow FPGA core is sensitive to fanout,\\nrouting, and unnecessary flop-side muxing. The stage registers still\\nsynchronously clear wide PC, instruction, operand, immediate, memory, and RVFI\\npayload fields on reset even though retirement and architectural side effects\\nare controlled by valid and compact control bits.\\n\\nThose reset muxes do not improve CoreMark IPC, but they can add high-fanout\\nreset routing and extra logic on the same pipeline registers used by the hot\\nexecute, memory, forwarding, and writeback paths.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Change the ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB pipeline registers to reset only the\\nfields that can cause visible side effects or false hazards: valid bits,\\ncompact control bits, destination registers, and memory masks as needed.\\nLeave wide payload fields such as pc, instr, operands, immediates, ALU result,\\nload data, and RVFI data as don't-care while invalid, then load them normally\\nwhen each stage captures a real instruction.\\n\\nKeep the IF PC, register file, and divider state reset behavior unchanged.\\nThis should reduce synchronous reset muxin...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Remove duplicate store-data payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The recent winning bench changes improved fitness by pruning dead control and reset plumbing rather than adding predictors or buffers. The current EX/MEM bundle still carries both write_data and rs2_val even though both are assigned the same post-forward rs2 operand and stay identical for stores, RVFI source reporting, and held divide completion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The recent winning bench changes improved fitness by pruning dead control and reset plumbing rather than adding predictors or buffers. The current EX/MEM bundle still carries both write_data and rs2_val even though both are assigned the same post-forward rs2 operand and stay identical for stores, RVFI source reporting, and held divide completion.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Delete the redundant ex_mem_t.write_data field and use ex_mem_t.rs2_val as the single canonical post-forward store-data operand in MEM. This removes a 32-bit pipeline payload register and its routing from the EX/MEM boundary while preserving store byte replication, RVFI rs2_rdata, forwarding behavior, memory ordering, trap handling, and the NRET=1 top-level contract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the duplicate write_data member from ex_mem_t and document rs2_val as the canonical post-forward store operand.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Stop assigning the removed EX/MEM write_data field; continue preserving the forwarded rs2 value in rs2_val for stores and RVFI.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Drive store byte replication from in.rs2_val instead of the removed write_data payload, preserving masks, misalignment gating, and RVFI mem_wdata.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the ...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Share EX add and compare cones\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The bench history shows the best improvements came from removing timing and\\nrouting pressure without adding new prediction, memory-ordering, or M-unit\\ncontrol. The current EX stage still spells out several equivalent 32-bit PC\\nadders and branch comparisons in separate expressions that feed redirect,\\npc_next, JAL link writeback, and RVFI pc_wdata. Even if synthesis shares some\\nof this logic, making the sharing explicit is a low-risk way to reduce the\\nbranch/redirect cone that CoreMark exercises heavily.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The bench history shows the best improvements came from removing timing and\\nrouting pressure without adding new prediction, memory-ordering, or M-unit\\ncontrol. The current EX stage still spells out several equivalent 32-bit PC\\nadders and branch comparisons in separate expressions that feed redirect,\\npc_next, JAL link writeback, and RVFI pc_wdata. Even if synthesis shares some\\nof this logic, making the sharing explicit is a low-risk way to reduce the\\nbranch/redirect cone that CoreMark exercises heavily.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/ex_stage.sv to compute common EX address terms once: pc_plus4,\\npc_imm_sum, and jalr_target. Reuse those wires for branch_target,\\njump_target, JAL/JALR link data, pc_next, and redirect_target instead of\\nrepeating in.pc + 4 and in.pc + imm expressions.\\n\\nAt the same time, rewrite the branch comparator around shared eq,\\nsigned_lt, and unsigned_lt primitives, using inversion for BNE/BGE/BGEU\\nrather than independent >= and != comparator expressions. This should trim\\nLUT depth and fanout on the EX redirect path without changing instruction\\nlatency, stall behavior, RVFI ordering, trap semantics, or the NRET=1 port\\ncontract.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Factor repeated PC adders an...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Split RVFI order counter\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent successful bench changes improved fitness by trimming timing and routing\\npressure without adding frontend prediction, memory bypasses, or new pipeline\\nstate. The top-level RVFI order counter still increments a full 64-bit value on\\nevery retirement, and that counter is synthesized into the FPGA build even\\nthough CoreMark only needs monotonic retirement numbering for checking.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent successful bench changes improved fitness by trimming timing and routing\\npressure without adding frontend prediction, memory bypasses, or new pipeline\\nstate. The top-level RVFI order counter still increments a full 64-bit value on\\nevery retirement, and that counter is synthesized into the FPGA build even\\nthough CoreMark only needs monotonic retirement numbering for checking.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the single 64-bit rvfi_order_q + 1 incrementer in rtl/core.sv with a\\nsplit low/high counter: increment a 32-bit low half every valid retirement and\\nincrement the high half only when the low half wraps. Drive the RVFI order port\\nfrom the concatenated halves, preserving reset-to-zero and strict +1 monotonic\\nordering across all retirements.\\n\\nThis keeps the NRET=1 port contract, retirement boundary, IPC, trap behavior,\\nand all memory behavior unchanged. If the current FPGA timing graph includes\\nthe 64-bit RVFI carry chain or its routing fanout, shortening it to two smaller\\ncounters should modestly raise median Fmax with essentially no CoreMark cycle\\ncost. If the order counter is not timing-relevant, the change should be nearly\\nneutral.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Split the RVFI order state into low/high halves and preserve the same concatenated order value on the channel-0 RVFI port.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped instruction replay predictor trained only by accepted\\ninstruction fetches. On an io_imemReady=1 fetch, record {PC tag, instruction}\\nin an 8-entry table. On a later io_imemReady=0 cycle, if the current PC hits\\nthe table, supply the cached instruction and treat fetch as effectively ready;\\notherwise keep the existing stall/NOP behavior.\\n\\nThis is not a branch target predictor and does not carry prediction metadata\\ninto EX. It attacks repeated hot-loop iStalls while avoiding the failed IF\\nbranch-predecode/BTB/RAS/backedge-repair paths. Because the instruction memory\\nis immutable in FPGA/cosim and formal ties io_imemReady high, a replay hit is\\narchitecturally the same instruction word previously observed for that PC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an 8-entry PC-tagged instruction replay predictor, fill it on accepted ready fetches,...\n  Line 32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Resetless IF replay payloads\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the accepted-fetch-only replay behavior exactly as-is, but reset only the\\nreplay_valid bits. Leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload registers\\nresetless because they are architecturally ignored whenever their valid bit is\\nclear and fully overwritten before any replay hit can occur.\\n\\nThis should trim synchronous reset muxing and reset-tree fanout introduced by\\nthe replay predictor without adding new prediction metadata, bypassing, or PC\\nmuxing. IPC should remain unchanged, while median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may rise\\nmodestly from lower IF-stage routing pressure.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Reset only replay_valid and the PC; leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload arrays resetless while preserving fill-on-imem-ready and replay-hit gating.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_de...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Trim IF replay tags to memory range\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The 8-entry IF replay table is the current strongest cycle-side win, but the\\nfollow-up attempts show the table is sensitive to routing: resetless payloads\\nand wider tables regressed, and the lesson points at compare/control cost\\nrather than capacity. Each replay entry still stores and compares pc[31:5],\\neven though valid instruction fetches for this benchmark contract are bounded\\nto the 1 MiB memory window.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 8-entry IF replay table is the current strongest cycle-side win, but the\\nfollow-up attempts show the table is sensitive to routing: resetless payloads\\nand wider tables regressed, and the lesson points at compare/control cost\\nrather than capacity. Each replay entry still stores and compares pc[31:5],\\neven though valid instruction fetches for this benchmark contract are bounded\\nto the 1 MiB memory window.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the accepted-fetch-only 8-entry replay table and its exact ready/hit\\nsemantics, but shrink replay_tag from pc[31:5] to pc[19:5]. Together with the\\nexisting pc[4:2] index, those bits uniquely identify every word-aligned fetch\\naddress in the legal [0x00000000, 0x00100000) instruction-memory region, so\\nCoreMark hit behavior and correctness for in-bounds execution are unchanged.\\n\\nThis removes 96 replay-tag flops and cuts each replay-hit comparator from 27\\nbits to 15 bits, directly attacking the IF-stage compare/routing pressure that\\nlikely limited the replay-table follow-ups. Formal keeps imemReady high, and\\nout-of-range PCs already violate the memory-bounds invariant rather than\\nrelying on replay tags for recovery.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Store and compare only replay_tag=pc[19:5] while preserving the 8-entry pc[4:2] index, fill-on-ready behavior, replay-on-stall h...\n  Line 38: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"Mask false load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw\\nsource fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode\\ndoes not consume rs2 or does not consume any register source. That creates\\noccasional one-cycle bubbles after loads for OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR, LUI, AUIPC,\\nJAL, FENCE, and other non-rs2 consumers whenever immediate bits alias the\\nload rd. Prior lessons show added bypass datapaths often cost too much, so\\nthe safest remaining IPC micro-opt is to remove only false stalls without\\nadding a new data path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw\\nsource fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode\\ndoes not consume rs2 or does not consume any register source. That creates\\noccasional one-cycle bubbles after loads for OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR, LUI, AUIPC,\\nJAL, FENCE, and other non-rs2 consumers whenever immediate bits alias the\\nload rd. Prior lessons show added bypass datapaths often cost too much, so\\nthe safest remaining IPC micro-opt is to remove only false stalls without\\nadding a new data path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small conservative source-use predecode to the hazard unit and gate the\\nload-use comparisons with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. R-type, branches, and stores\\nkeep both-source behavior, so a load feeding store data still stalls exactly\\nas it does today; OP-IMM, LOAD, and JALR only check rs1; LUI, AUIPC, JAL, and\\nFENCE check neither. Unknown or potentially source-reading encodings should\\ndefault to conservative checking so illegal-instruction RVFI source reporting\\nand trap behavior are not weakened.\\n\\nThis differs from the failed late load-store bypass attempt by not adding a\\nMEM-stage store-data mux or changing forwarding. It should recover a modest\\nnumber of CoreMark bubbles with only a small opcode decod...","metadata":{"matches":15,"truncated":false},"title":"category: micro_opt|\"category\": \"micro_opt\"|micro_opt|hyp-20260512-003-r10s2|hyp-20260512-001-r6s0|hyp-20260512-001-r7s0","time":{"start":1778615793155,"end":1778615793164}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c60b39e293c9d6c016a0385f1015c8194b958b7623d3a10d9"}},"id":"prt_e1dc33601001M71jUCWQwJIqVj","sessionID":"ses_1e23d079bffeuSJQ2dbzbV0CwL","messageID":"msg_e1dc2f8b7001RvtETq9ICkp8W4"}}
