{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778615886359,"sessionID":"ses_1e23d079bffeuSJQ2dbzbV0CwL","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_jasACZq1SwUb81NHfT1biqIq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r14s0\n+title: \"Simplify IF replay muxing\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The accepted-fetch IF replay table is the current best cycle-side improvement,\n+  but later replay follow-ups regressed when they added capacity, training logic,\n+  or extra redirect filtering. The remaining promising micro-opt is therefore to\n+  keep the exact replay behavior while reducing the mux and compare pressure that\n+  now sits on the fetch-to-decode path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the replay tag compare only decides whether a\n+  stalled fetch is usable, while the instruction-data mux selects directly between\n+  live imem_data when io_imemReady is high and the indexed replay word when it is\n+  low. On a miss with io_imemReady low, the existing imem_stall/flush path still\n+  forces a NOP, so stale replay data is never decoded.\n+\n+  This should preserve the successful 8-entry accepted-fetch replay semantics,\n+  reset behavior, redirect priority, RVFI-visible instruction stream, and NRET=1\n+  contract, but remove one replay_hit-controlled 32-bit mux level from the common\n+  IF instruction path. Also drop redundant redirect selection from the sequential\n+  pc+4 increment term if it remains syntactically present, because redirect is\n+  already handled by the priority PC update branch.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Factor replay_match/replay_hit from fetch_instr selection, use io_imemReady as the direct data mux select, and remove any redundant redirect muxing from the pc+4 increment path without changing fill-on-ready replay behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r14s0.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,28 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r14s0\n+title: \"Simplify IF replay muxing\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The accepted-fetch IF replay table is the current best cycle-side improvement,\n+  but later replay follow-ups regressed when they added capacity, training logic,\n+  or extra redirect filtering. The remaining promising micro-opt is therefore to\n+  keep the exact replay behavior while reducing the mux and compare pressure that\n+  now sits on the fetch-to-decode path.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the replay tag compare only decides whether a\n+  stalled fetch is usable, while the instruction-data mux selects directly between\n+  live imem_data when io_imemReady is high and the indexed replay word when it is\n+  low. On a miss with io_imemReady low, the existing imem_stall/flush path still\n+  forces a NOP, so stale replay data is never decoded.\n+\n+  This should preserve the successful 8-entry accepted-fetch replay semantics,\n+  reset behavior, redirect priority, RVFI-visible instruction stream, and NRET=1\n+  contract, but remove one replay_hit-controlled 32-bit mux level from the common\n+  IF instruction path. Also drop redundant redirect selection from the sequential\n+  pc+4 increment term if it remains syntactically present,