after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only successful predictor result so far was the tiny instruction-fetch\\nreplay table, because it converts random hot-loop instruction-bus stalls into\\nuseful decode cycles without adding branch target lookup, prediction repair,\\nor EX-stage metadata. CoreMark's timed working set is larger than eight\\nfetch-table slots, so direct-mapped conflicts can still turn repeated PCs\\nback into imem stalls even after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the IF-stage instruction replay predictor from 8 direct-mapped entries\\nto 16 direct-mapped entries while keeping the exact same training and use\\ndiscipline: fill only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, replay only when\\nio_imemReady is low and the current PC tag hits, and leave all branch/jump\\nprediction behavior unchanged. This should reduce replay conflict misses in\\nCoreMark hot loops under the 22% random iStall model while avoiding the\\ntarget-PC muxing and prediction-repair metadata that made earlier branch\\npredictors regress. The added hardware is one more index bit and a modestly\\nlarger tag/instruction array, so the expected gain is smaller than the first\\nreplay predictor but still plausible.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Increase the PC-tagged instruction replay predictor to 16 direct-mapped entries, preserving fill-on-ready and replay-on-stall semantics.\"}...\n  Line 35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Trim IF replay tags to memory range\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The 8-entry IF replay table is the current strongest cycle-side win, but the\\nfollow-up attempts show the table is sensitive to routing: resetless payloads\\nand wider tables regressed, and the lesson points at compare/control cost\\nrather than capacity. Each replay entry still stores and compares pc[31:5],\\neven though valid instruction fetches for this benchmark contract are bounded\\nto the 1 MiB memory window.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 8-entry IF replay table is the current strongest cycle-side win, but the\\nfollow-up attempts show the table is sensitive to routing: resetless payloads\\nand wider tables regressed, and the lesson points at compare/control cost\\nrather than capacity. Each replay entry still stores and compares pc[31:5],\\neven though valid instruction fetches for this benchmark contract are bounded\\nto the 1 MiB memory window.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the accepted-fetch-only 8-entry replay table and its exact ready/hit\\nsemantics, but shrink replay_tag from pc[31:5] to pc[19:5]. Together with the\\nexisting pc[4:2] index, those bits uniquely identify every word-aligned fetch\\naddress in the legal [0x00000000, 0x00100000) instruction-memory region, so\\nCoreMark hit behavior and correctness for in-bounds execution are unchanged.\\n\\nThis removes 96 replay-tag flops and cuts each replay-hit comparator from 27\\nbits to 15 bits, directly attacking the IF-stage compare/routing pressure that\\nlikely limited the replay-table follow-ups. Formal keeps imemReady high, and\\nout-of-range PCs already violate the memory-bounds invariant rather than\\nrelying on replay tags for recovery.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Store and compare only replay_tag=pc[19:5] while preserving the 8-entry pc[4:2] index, fill-on-ready behavior, replay-on-stall h...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Warm replay during backend stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 8-entry IF replay table produced the largest recent improvement by\\nconverting random instruction-bus stalls into useful hot-loop instructions.\\nFollow-up attempts to widen or reset-retime the table regressed, which points\\naway from adding capacity on the fetch critical path and toward improving how\\noften the existing table is populated.\\n\\nBackend stalls from dmem backpressure, load-use bubbles, and iterative divide\\nalready stop decode from consuming the current fetch slot. Those cycles can be\\nused to issue harmless sequential instruction fetches and train the replay\\ntable, because instruction memory is immutable and wrong-path replay fills do\\nnot affect architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 8-entry IF replay table produced the largest recent improvement by\\nconverting random instruction-bus stalls into useful hot-loop instructions.\\nFollow-up attempts to widen or reset-retime the table regressed, which points\\naway from adding capacity on the fetch critical path and toward improving how\\noften the existing table is populated.\\n\\nBackend stalls from dmem backpressure, load-use bubbles, and iterative divide\\nalready stop decode from consuming the current fetch slot. Those cycles can be\\nused to issue harmless sequential instruction fetches and train the replay\\ntable, because instruction memory is immutable and wrong-path replay fills do\\nnot affect architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an opportunistic replay warmer inside IF. When the architectural PC is\\nheld for a non-redirect backend stall and the instruction bus is ready, drive\\nio_imemAddr from a small sequential prefetch cursor instead of the held PC and\\nfill the existing replay table with the returned instruction. Keep out.pc,\\nRVFI-visible instruction flow, redirect handling, and decode consumption tied\\nto the architectural PC; the wa...\n  Line 37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Line-packed ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only predictor that improved this bench core was the tiny instruction-fetch replay table, which converts random hot-loop iStall cycles into useful decoded instructions without branch target prediction or EX repair metadata. Follow-up attempts to widen the table or remove payload resets regressed, suggesting the remaining replay cost is tag/control routing rather than capacity or reset muxing.\\n\\nA predictor refinement should therefore keep the accepted-fetch-only replay semantics but reduce the fetch-stage compare and tag storage pressure that now sits on every stalled fetch decision.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only predictor that improved this bench core was the tiny instruction-fetch replay table, which converts random hot-loop iStall cycles into useful decoded instructions without branch target prediction or EX repair metadata. Follow-up attempts to widen the table or remove payload resets regressed, suggesting the remaining replay cost is tag/control routing rather than capacity or reset muxing.\\n\\nA predictor refinement should therefore keep the accepted-fetch-only replay semantics but reduce the fetch-stage compare and tag storage pressure that now sits on every stalled fetch decision.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Repack the current 8-entry single-word replay table into four two-word replay lines. Each line stores one full PC tag, two instruction words, and per-word valid bits; accepted fetches fill only the addressed half, clearing the sibling valid bit when a different tag replaces the line. On io_imemReady=0, a replay hit still requires a full tag match plus the selected half valid bit, then supplies the cached immutable instruction and asserts imem_effective_ready exactly as today.\\n\\nThis preserves the successful no-branch-prediction replay model and the NRET=1 RVFI contract while halving the number of stored tags and tag-select ro...\n  Line 38: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r13s0\", \"title\": \"Mask false load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw\\nsource fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode\\ndoes not consume rs2 or does not consume any register source. That creates\\noccasional one-cycle bubbles after loads for OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR, LUI, AUIPC,\\nJAL, FENCE, and other non-rs2 consumers whenever immediate bits alias the\\nload rd. Prior lessons show added bypass datapaths often cost too much, so\\nthe safest remaining IPC micro-opt is to remove only false stalls without\\nadding a new data path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both raw\\nsource fields of the following instruction, even when the following opcode\\ndoes not consume rs2 or does not consume any register source. That creates\\noccasional one-cycle bubbles after loads for OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR, LUI, AUIPC,\\nJAL, FENCE, and other non-rs2 consumers whenever immediate bits alias the\\nload rd. Prior lessons show added bypass datapaths often cost too much, so\\nthe safest remaining IPC micro-opt is to remove only false stalls without\\nadding a new data path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small conservative source-use predecode to the hazard unit and gate the\\nload-use comparisons with uses_rs1 and uses_rs2. R-type, branches, and stores\\nkeep both-source behavior, so a load feeding store data still stalls exactly\\nas it does today; OP-IMM, LOAD, and JALR only check rs1; LUI, AUIPC, JAL, and\\nFENCE check neither. Unknown or potentially source-reading encodings should\\ndefault to conservative checking so illegal-instruction RVFI source reporting\\nand trap behavior are not weakened.\\n\\nThis differs from the failed late load-store bypass attempt by not adding a\\nMEM-stage store-data mux or changing forwarding. It should recover a modest\\nnumber of CoreMark bubbles with only a small opcode decod...\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"Register fetch-decode boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current bench core still has an unusually long frontend timing path: the IF\\nstage emits a combinational IF/ID payload, so io_imemData or replay-table data\\nflows through the fetch mux, decoder, immediate generator, register-file read\\naddresses, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Recent structural history\\nshows that adding predictors, queues, wider replay, and bypass paths usually\\nlost timing, while pruning existing stage plumbing helped. A minimal pipeline\\nboundary is therefore a better structural bet than adding more speculation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current bench core still has an unusually long frontend timing path: the IF\\nstage emits a combinational IF/ID payload, so io_imemData or replay-table data\\nflows through the fetch mux, decoder, immediate generator, register-file read\\naddresses, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Recent structural history\\nshows that adding predictors, queues, wider replay, and bypass paths usually\\nlost timing, while pruning existing stage plumbing helped. A minimal pipeline\\nboundary is therefore a better structural bet than adding more speculation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a real registered IF/ID boundary owned by the fetch stage, while keeping\\nthe existing 8-entry accepted-fetch replay table and NRET=1 retirement contract.\\nFetch should capture pc/instruction/valid only when the current fetch is usable\\nvia io_imemReady or a replay hit and ID can accept it; redirects flush the IF/ID\\nregister and update the PC to the resolved target. ID then decodes only the\\nregistered IF/ID payload, shortening the common FPGA path from instruction data\\nto decoded ID/EX controls and regfile source reads.\\n\\nThis will likely add one extra bubble on taken redirects compared with the\\ncurrent combinational IF/ID design, so the implementation should keep the\\nbranch/hazard machinery conservati...\n  Line 40: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r13s2\", \"title\": \"Redirect-filtered replay training\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only predictor that has improved this core is the tiny accepted-fetch\\ninstruction replay table, because it hides random hot-loop iStalls without\\nadding branch target lookup or EX repair metadata. The current IF code still\\nfills the direct-mapped replay entry on any io_imemReady cycle, including the\\ncycle an EX redirect kills the fetched sequential wrong-path instruction.\\nIn tight taken loops, those wrong-path fall-through fills can repeatedly\\nevict useful loop-body replay entries with the same pc[4:2] index.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only predictor that has improved this core is the tiny accepted-fetch\\ninstruction replay table, because it hides random hot-loop iStalls without\\nadding branch target lookup or EX repair metadata. The current IF code still\\nfills the direct-mapped replay entry on any io_imemReady cycle, including the\\ncycle an EX redirect kills the fetched sequential wrong-path instruction.\\nIn tight taken loops, those wrong-path fall-through fills can repeatedly\\nevict useful loop-body replay entries with the same pc[4:2] index.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the existing 8-entry replay predictor lookup and hit semantics exactly\\nas they are, but train the table only when the fetched instruction is not\\nbeing killed by a redirect/flush. On an EX redirect, update the architectural\\nPC to the target as today but skip the replay fill for the wrong-path word at\\nthe old PC. If that fall-through path is later executed for real, it will be\\nfetched and trained on a non-redirect cycle.\\n\\nThis should improve replay hit quality for CoreMark's repeated taken loops\\nwithout adding a new IF tag compare, target mux, branch predecode path, or\\nprediction metadata. The change is intentionally small: it may recover a few\\niStall bubbles by reducing direct-mapped pollution while preserving Fmax and\\nall NRET=1 RVFI behavior.\\n\", \"expec...\n  Line 41: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r14s0\", \"title\": \"Simplify IF replay muxing\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The accepted-fetch IF replay table is the current best cycle-side improvement,\\nbut later replay follow-ups regressed when they added capacity, training logic,\\nor extra redirect filtering. The remaining promising micro-opt is therefore to\\nkeep the exact replay behavior while reducing the mux and compare pressure that\\nnow sits on the fetch-to-decode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The accepted-fetch IF replay table is the current best cycle-side improvement,\\nbut later replay follow-ups regressed when they added capacity, training logic,\\nor extra redirect filtering. The remaining promising micro-opt is therefore to\\nkeep the exact replay behavior while reducing the mux and compare pressure that\\nnow sits on the fetch-to-decode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refactor rtl/if_stage.sv so the replay tag compare only decides whether a\\nstalled fetch is usable, while the instruction-data mux selects directly between\\nlive imem_data when io_imemReady is high and the indexed replay word when it is\\nlow. On a miss with io_imemReady low, the existing imem_stall/flush path still\\nforces a NOP, so stale replay data is never decoded.\\n\\nThis should preserve the successful 8-entry accepted-fetch replay semantics,\\nreset behavior, redirect priority, RVFI-visible instruction stream, and NRET=1\\ncontract, but remove one replay_hit-controlled 32-bit mux level from the common\\nIF instruction path. Also drop redundant redirect selection from the sequential\\npc+4 increment term if it remains syntactically present, because redirect is\\nalready handled by the priority PC update branch.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Factor replay_match/replay_hit from fetch_instr selection, use io_imemReady as the direct data mux select, and remove any redundant redirect muxing from the pc+4 inc...\n  Line 42: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\", \"title\": \"Valid-gated fetch bubbles\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffers, or wider replay state generally regressed because they put more muxing and control on already-sensitive paths. The successful changes instead pruned existing pipeline state or let the accepted-fetch replay table hide iStalls without branch-repair metadata.\\n\\nThe current frontend still forces every flush, redirect, or imem-miss bubble through a 32-bit NOP mux before decode. That mux sits directly on the imem/replay-data to decoder, immediate generator, regfile-address, and ID/EX capture path even though invalid instructions never retire.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffers, or wider replay state generally regressed because they put more muxing and control on already-sensitive paths. The successful changes instead pruned existing pipeline state or let the accepted-fetch replay table hide iStalls without branch-repair metadata.\\n\\nThe current frontend still forces every flush, redirect, or imem-miss bubble through a 32-bit NOP mux before decode. That mux sits directly on the imem/replay-data to decoder, immediate generator, regfile-address, and ID/EX capture path even though invalid instructions never retire.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Represent frontend bubbles with the existing valid bit instead of replacing the instruction word with ADDI x0,x0,0. IF should always pass the fetched or replayed instruction bits forward and set out.valid low for flush/redirect/imem-miss cycles. ID should zero side-effect controls and destination metadata whenever in.valid is low, and the load-use hazard should be gated by IF/ID and ID/EX validity so stale invalid instruction bits cannot create false interlocks.\\n\\nThis removes a normal-cycle 32-bit instruction mux from the fetch-to-decode cone and moves correctness onto compact valid/control gat...\n  Line 43: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r14s2\", \"title\": \"Folded-index ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only predictor that has produced a large bench improvement is the accepted-fetch instruction replay table, because it hides random hot-loop iStalls without branch-target lookup, predecode, or EX repair metadata. Follow-up replay changes that widened the table, repacked lines, warmed during backend stalls, or filtered redirect fills all regressed, so the next predictor step should preserve the same simple lookup semantics and avoid adding new storage depth or control paths.\\n\\nThe current 8-entry table is indexed directly by pc[4:2], so instructions separated by 32-byte strides always evict each other. CoreMark loop bodies and call-heavy code can easily contain hot PCs with that spacing, causing replay misses even after each instruction has been fetched successfully before.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only predictor that has produced a large bench improvement is the accepted-fetch instruction replay table, because it hides random hot-loop iStalls without branch-target lookup, predecode, or EX repair metadata. Follow-up replay changes that widened the table, repacked lines, warmed during backend stalls, or filtered redirect fills all regressed, so the next predictor step should preserve the same simple lookup semantics and avoid adding new storage depth or control paths.\\n\\nThe current 8-entry table is indexed directly by pc[4:2], so instructions separated by 32-byte strides always evict each other. CoreMark loop bodies and call-heavy code can easily contain hot PCs with that spacing, causing replay misses even after each instruction has been fetched successfully before.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the 8-entry accepted-fetch replay predictor exactly the same size and keep its fill-on-io_imemReady, replay-only-when-io_imemReady-is-low semantics, but replace the direct pc[4:2] index with a cheap folded hash such as pc[4:2] ^ pc[7:5]. Keep t...","metadata":{"matches":43,"truncated":false},"title":"micro_opt|category.*micro|hyp-20260512","time":{"start":1778616526819,"end":1778616526835}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b951286fca1271b016a0388ceb2a4819394c56104cfd76c3c"}},"id":"prt_e1dce67e1001657UrNtLE1uaQo","sessionID":"ses_1e231c63affeCxs3BPM8Ye0FON","messageID":"msg_e1dce3a17001ZT9KieArBYZncw"}}
