{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778610459157,"sessionID":"ses_1e292bd05ffeoELacAG8c0IagX","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_MIOMdAuWk0vY8OSZUcpT6f00","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r10s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r10s1\n+title: \"Split writeback bypass from regfile reads\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The strongest positive bench changes have removed fanout and muxing from existing pipeline paths rather than adding predictors, buffers, or extra memory machinery. The register file still has write-first read bypass muxes on both asynchronous read ports, so every ID-stage source read carries same-cycle WB address compares and write-data muxing even though most dynamic reads do not hit the current WB instruction.\n+\n+  Prior resetless-regfile work showed the reset tree was not the interesting part of this block; the remaining structural target is the read/write bypass coupling itself. Moving the rare same-cycle WB dependency into the existing EX forwarding network should shorten the imem-data-to-ID/EX register-file read path without changing CoreMark CPI.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Make rtl/reg_file.sv a simple 2R1W architectural array: x0 remains hardwired to zero, writes remain synchronous, but read ports no longer mux in same-cycle w_data. Add a one-cycle registered WB-bypass source in core.sv that captures each real WB write, extend forward_unit.sv to select it as the lowest-priority EX forwarding source, and extend ex_stage.sv operand muxes to consume that source.\n+\n+  This preserves correctness for instructions whose ID read coincides with an older instruction's WB write, because the consumer reaches EX one cycle later and can receive the captured WB value there. Keep EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding priority unchanged, including the invalid-but-held MEM/WB payload required during dmem stalls, so this avoids the prior MEM/WB-hold forwarding regression while removing two wide write-first muxes from the register-file read path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove same-cycle write-first muxing from the asynchronous read ports while preserving x0 and synchronous writes.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Add a registered previous-WB bypass source and wire it into the forwarding and EX operand paths without changing NRET=1 RVFI.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add lowest-priority previous-WB comparisons after the existing EX/MEM and MEM/WB forwarding sources.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Extend the operand forwarding muxes to accept the new registered previous-WB source.\"\n+  - file: test/test_wb_bypass.py\n+    description: \"Add dependency tests covering distance-three WB hazards and stalled consumers to lock down the new bypass contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r10s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r10s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r10s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r10s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r10s1\n+title: \"Split writeback bypass from regfile reads\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The strongest positive bench changes have removed fanout and muxing from existing pipeline paths rather than adding predictors, buffers, or extra memory machinery. The register file still has write-firs