{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778614403594,"sessionID":"ses_1e25474a0ffeoXdwBn3Yq7E6gl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_inJlCbvaz1VQoGlS7ANDOgLx","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Register fetch-decode boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current bench core still has an unusually long frontend timing path: the IF\n+  stage emits a combinational IF/ID payload, so io_imemData or replay-table data\n+  flows through the fetch mux, decoder, immediate generator, register-file read\n+  addresses, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Recent structural history\n+  shows that adding predictors, queues, wider replay, and bypass paths usually\n+  lost timing, while pruning existing stage plumbing helped. A minimal pipeline\n+  boundary is therefore a better structural bet than adding more speculation.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Insert a real registered IF/ID boundary owned by the fetch stage, while keeping\n+  the existing 8-entry accepted-fetch replay table and NRET=1 retirement contract.\n+  Fetch should capture pc/instruction/valid only when the current fetch is usable\n+  via io_imemReady or a replay hit and ID can accept it; redirects flush the IF/ID\n+  register and update the PC to the resolved target. ID then decodes only the\n+  registered IF/ID payload, shortening the common FPGA path from instruction data\n+  to decoded ID/EX controls and regfile source reads.\n+\n+  This will likely add one extra bubble on taken redirects compared with the\n+  current combinational IF/ID design, so the implementation should keep the\n+  branch/hazard machinery conservative and avoid any new prediction metadata.\n+  The expected gain is higher Fmax from a true fetch/decode cut, not better IPC.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Convert the combinational IF/ID output into a real registered fetch/decode boundary, preserving the 8-entry accepted-fetch replay table and flushing on redirects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Decode the registered IF/ID payload and keep ID/EX hold/bubble behavior correct for backend stalls, load-use hazards, and redirects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust stall and flush control for the new IF/ID register so accepted fetches are not lost and wrong-path registered instructions are killed precisely.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the revised frontend control while leaving the core top-level IO and single-channel RVFI retirement contract unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,36 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Register fetch-decode boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current bench core still has an unusually long frontend timing path: the IF\n+  stage emits a combinational IF/ID payload, so io_imemData or replay-table data\n+  flows through the fetch mux, decoder, immediate generator, register-file read\n+  addresses, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Recent structural history\n+  shows that adding predictors, queues, wider replay, and bypass paths usually\n+  lost timing, while pru