{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778615893698,"sessionID":"ses_1e23d0805ffewgsIGhc3LDLwLI","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_rfBCE9dnrbir9u8kx1la7Bj8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\n2: title: \"Valid-gated fetch bubbles\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   Prior structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffers, or wider replay state generally regressed because they put more muxing and control on already-sensitive paths. The successful changes instead pruned existing pipeline state or let the accepted-fetch replay table hide iStalls without branch-repair metadata.\n6: \n7:   The current frontend still forces every flush, redirect, or imem-miss bubble through a 32-bit NOP mux before decode. That mux sits directly on the imem/replay-data to decoder, immediate generator, regfile-address, and ID/EX capture path even though invalid instructions never retire.\n8: hypothesis: |\n9:   Represent frontend bubbles with the existing valid bit instead of replacing the instruction word with ADDI x0,x0,0. IF should always pass the fetched or replayed instruction bits forward and set out.valid low for flush/redirect/imem-miss cycles. ID should zero side-effect controls and destination metadata whenever in.valid is low, and the load-use hazard should be gated by IF/ID and ID/EX validity so stale invalid instruction bits cannot create false interlocks.\n10: \n11:   This removes a normal-cycle 32-bit instruction mux from the fetch-to-decode cone and moves correctness onto compact valid/control gating. CoreMark IPC should be unchanged, while Tang Nano 20K Fmax may improve by shortening the path that now includes replay-hit data, NOP selection, decode, immediate generation, and ID/EX control capture.\n12: expected_impact:\n13:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n14:   confidence: medium\n15: changes:\n16:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n17:     description: \"Stop muxing NOP onto out.instr for bubbles; drive fetched/replayed bits unchanged and use out.valid to mark flush, redirect, and imem-miss bubbles.\"\n18:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n19:     description: \"When in.valid is low, capture zero side-effect controls and destination metadata while leaving invalid payload fields architecturally ignored.\"\n20:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n21:     description: \"Gate load-use detection with IF/ID and ID/EX validity so invalid instruction bits cannot cause false stalls after removing NOP injection.\"\n22:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n23:     description: \"Wire the existing IF/ID and ID/EX valid bits into the hazard unit without changing the NRET=1 top-level RVFI port contract.\"\n\n(End of file - total 23 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\ntitle: \"Valid-gated fetch bubbles\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  Prior structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffers, or wider replay state generally regressed because they put more muxing and control on already-sensitive paths. The successful changes instead pruned existing pipeline state or let the accepted-fetch replay table hide iStalls without branch-repair metadata.\n\n  The current frontend still forces every flush, redirect, or imem-miss bubble through a 32-bit NOP mux before decode. That mux sits directly on the imem/replay-data to decoder, immediate generator, regfile-address, and ID/EX capture path even though invalid instructions never retire.\nhypothesis: |\n  Represent frontend bubbles with the existing valid bit instead of replacing the instruction word with ADDI x0,x0,0. IF should always pass the fetched or replayed instruction bits forward and set out.valid low for flush/redirect/imem-miss cycles. ID should zero side-effect controls and destination metadata whenever in.valid is low, and the load-use hazard should be gated by IF/ID and ID/EX validity so stale invalid instruction bits cannot create false interlocks.\n\n  This removes a normal-cycle 32-bit instruction mux from the fetch-to-decode cone and moves correctness onto compact valid/control gating. CoreMark IPC should be unchanged, while Tang Nano 20K Fmax may improve by shortening the path that now includes replay-hit data, NOP selection, decode, immediate generation, and ID/EX control capture.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Stop muxing NOP onto out.instr for bubbles; drive fetched/replayed bits unchanged and use out.valid to mark flush, redirect, and imem-miss bubbles.\"\n  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n    description: \"When in.valid is low, capture zero side-effect controls and destination metadata while leaving invalid payload fields architecturally ignored.\"\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r14s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778615893676,"end":1778615893697}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05e1a0958f7c244c016a038655492c81948fe8f291cf96ad64"}},"id":"prt_e1dc4bd85001UzG1t8usjGA05p","sessionID":"ses_1e23d0805ffewgsIGhc3LDLwLI","messageID":"msg_e1dc49aeb0015qbxNhUD4j7O8z"}}
