med loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple fetch with skid queue\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a small two-entry instruction skid/prefetch queue between the fetch PC\\nand ID. The fetch side advances and enqueues whenever io_imemReady is high and\\nthe queue is not full; the decode side consumes only when the existing backend\\nhazard logic allows ID to advance. Redirects flush the queue and restart fetch\\nat the resolved target, preserving precise RVFI retirement and the NRET=1 port\\ncontract.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should hide a fraction of random iStall cycles\\nbehind dmem stalls, load-use bubbles, and divide busy cycles, while adding only\\na shallow FIFO and PC muxes instead of putting branch predecode on the\\nimem_data-to-next_pc critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single PC-to-ID combinational fetch path with ...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"One-entry RAM store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current in-order pipeline freezes behind every STORE whenever io_dmemReady\\nis low, even though most stores do not produce a value needed by the following\\ninstruction. In the tournament cosim mode dmem sees random backpressure, so\\nCoreMark pays avoidable full-pipeline bubbles on ordinary RAM stores.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts put new logic on the fetch path or tried to decouple\\nthe whole M-extension unit. A narrower backend store buffer should attack a\\ncommon stall source while leaving fetch, branch resolution, RVFI width, and the\\nworking iterative divider structure unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current in-order pipeline freezes behind every STORE whenever io_dmemReady\\nis low, even though most stores do not produce a value needed by the following\\ninstruction. In the tournament cosim mode dmem sees random backpressure, so\\nCoreMark pays avoidable full-pipeline bubbles on ordinary RAM stores.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts put new logic on the fetch path or tried to decouple\\nthe whole M-extension unit. A narrower backend store buffer should attack a\\ncommon stall source while leaving fetch, branch resolution, RVFI width, and the\\nworking iterative divider structure unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry write buffer for aligned, non-MMIO RAM stores. When a store\\nreaches MEM and the dmem bus is not ready, capture its address, byte mask, and\\nreplicated write data into the buffer, retire the store once architecturally\\nenqueued, and let younger non-memory instructions continue. Drain the buffer\\nto dmem as soon as io_dmemReady returns.\\n\\nPreserve ordering by stalling any younger load/store while the buffer is full\\nunless the pending store has drained, and keep UART/timing-marker MMIO stores\\nunbuffered so CoreMark brackets and output timing remain tied to real bus\\nacceptance. This should hide a fraction of random dmem ...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Split high-half multiplier\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a simple single-cycle low-32-bit product, because that is the\\nmultiply form most likely used by compiled CoreMark matrix code. Move only\\nMULH, MULHU, and MULHSU into a small iterative high-half multiply unit with\\nthe same start/done/ack discipline already proven necessary for the divider.\\n\\nIn the core build, EX should treat the high-half multiply variants like the\\nexisting iterative divider: hold ID/EX while the unit runs, latch the original\\nforwarded operands for RVFI, and emit exactly one EX/MEM res...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Pipelined full multiplier unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best measured improvement came from removing cold divide/remainder logic from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path. The remaining wide arithmetic limiter is the\\nsingle-cycle RV32M multiplier cone: the ALU still builds multiple 64-bit products\\nin the same result path used by ordinary adds, branches, address generation, and\\nstores. Prior high-half-only attempts regressed because low-half MUL stayed in\\nthat common cone, so the critical path was not structurally removed.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best measured improvement came from removing cold divide/remainder logic from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path. The remaining wide arithmetic limiter is the\\nsingle-cycle RV32M multiplier cone: the ALU still builds multiple 64-bit products\\nin the same result path used by ordinary adds, branches, address generation, and\\nstores. Prior high-half-only attempts regressed because low-half MUL stayed in\\nthat common cone, so the critical path was not structurally removed.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move all real MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU execution out of rtl/alu.sv into a dedicated\\ntwo-cycle multiplier unit built from registered 16x16 partial products followed\\nby a registered combine/sign-select stage. EX should treat every real multiply\\nlike the existing iterative divider: latch the forwarded operands, assert a\\nbusy stall while the unit is active, and emit exactly one EX/MEM result with the\\noriginal operands preserved for RVFI.\\n\\nThis pays one extra cycle on CoreMark multiply instructions, but it removes the\\n32x32/64-bit product cone from the common single-cycle RV32I execute path and\\nshould improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax more than the modest MUL CPI loss. Under\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the existing algebraic substitutions single-cycle so\\nthe formal harness remains tractable and consistent with the spec files.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\"...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Resetless LUTRAM register file\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\\n\\nRetargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\\n\\nRetargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild rtl/reg_file.sv as resetless storage for x1-x31, with x0 represented only by constant-zero read behavior and dropped writes. Preserve the same two asynchronous read ports, one synchronous write port, and same-cycle write-first bypass, but remove the per-bit synchronous reset from the data array.\\n\\nUse deterministic power-up initialization if needed for simulation/FPGA startup, but do not clear the data array through reset. This should let Yosys map the register file to distributed RAM or at least smaller unreset storage, cutting reset/write mux depth and routing...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Valid-gated resetless pipeline payloads\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\\n\\nThe ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\\n\\nThe ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the inter-stage pipeline registers to a valid-gated reset discipline: reset and flush only the valid bits plus control fields that can cause side effects, while leaving bulk data payload flops resetless. Gate redirect, memory request, writeback, forwarding, and ...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"MEM-to-EX load bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline pays a one-cycle load-use interlock whenever a load in\\nEX feeds either raw source field of the following instruction. CoreMark's hot\\nloops are load-heavy, and the successful recent changes show that this core\\nis already Fmax-competitive enough that recovering real CPI bubbles may be a\\nbetter structural bet than adding more prediction or buffering state.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added fetch queues, predictors, store buffers,\\nor multi-cycle multiply control regressed, so this proposal keeps the pipeline\\nshape and NRET=1 RVFI contract intact while only adding a local load-result\\nbypass around the existing MEM/EX boundary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline pays a one-cycle load-use interlock whenever a load in\\nEX feeds either raw source field of the following instruction. CoreMark's hot\\nloops are load-heavy, and the successful recent changes show that this core\\nis already Fmax-competitive enough that recovering real CPI bubbles may be a\\nbetter structural bet than adding more prediction or buffering state.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added fetch queues, predictors, store buffers,\\nor multi-cycle multiply control regressed, so this proposal keeps the pipeline\\nshape and NRET=1 RVFI contract intact while only adding a local load-result\\nbypass around the existing MEM/EX boundary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a same-cycle MEM-to-EX forwarding path for loads. When a load is in MEM\\nand its data is available, feed the MEM-stage sign/zero-extended load result\\ninto the existing EX operand forwarding mux instead of forwarding the load's\\naddress from EX/MEM. Then remove the blanket load-use stall for consumers\\nthat can safely wait under the existing dmem stall mechanism.\\n\\nKeep correctness conservative for control-flow consumers: if a dependent\\nbranch or JALR would use a load value before the dmem response is...\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Registered writeback result path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent winning changes improved fitness by removing late pipeline baggage\\nrather than adding predictors, queues, or buffers. The current MEM/WB stage\\nstill carries both alu_result and read_data plus a mem_to_reg control bit,\\nthen rebuilds the final writeback value through a combinational mux in WB.\\nThat mux output fans out to the register file, MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding, and\\nRVFI rd_wdata, so it can sit on the common dependent-instruction path even\\nthough the load-versus-ALU choice is already known when MEM/WB captures.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent winning changes improved fitness by removing late pipeline baggage\\nrather than adding predictors, queues, or buffers. The current MEM/WB stage\\nstill carries both alu_result and read_data plus a mem_to_reg control bit,\\nthen rebuilds the final writeback value through a combinational mux in WB.\\nThat mux output fans out to the register file, MEM/WB-to-EX forwarding, and\\nRVFI rd_wdata, so it can sit on the common dependent-instruction path even\\nthough the load-versus-ALU choice is already known when MEM/WB captures.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move final writeback-value selection into the MEM stage and store a single\\nregistered wb_data field in MEM/WB. Remove the separate MEM/WB read_data,\\nalu_result, and mem_to_reg payload/control used only to recreate that value\\none cycle later, and make wb_stage a simple valid/reg_write gate around the\\nregistered result.\\n\\nThis keeps pipeline timing, NRET=1 RVFI behavior, memory ordering, dmem-stall\\nhold semantics, and CoreMark instruction count unchanged while shortening the\\nMEM/WB-to-EX forwarding cone and trimming one 32-bit late-stage payload. The\\nchange follows the successful control-pruning direction but avoids the r8s0\\nmistake of increasing store-data fanout, because it only collapses mutually\\nexclusive writeback-result copies after MEM has alre...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Split writeback bypass from regfile reads\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest positive bench changes have removed fanout and muxing from existing pipeline paths rather than adding predictors, buffers, or extra memory machinery. The register file still has write-first read bypass muxes on both asynchronous read ports, so every ID-stage source read carries same-cycle WB address compares and write-data muxing even though most dynamic reads do not hit the current WB instruction.\\n\\nPrior resetless-regfile work showed the reset tree was not the interesting part of this block; the remaining structural target is the read/write bypass coupling itself. Moving the rare same-cycle WB dependency into the existing EX forwarding network should shorten the imem-data-to-ID/EX register-file read path without changing CoreMark CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest positive bench changes have removed fanout and muxing from existing pipeline paths rather than adding predictors, buffers, or extra memory machinery. The register file still has write-first read bypass muxes on both asynchronous read ports, so every ID-stage source read carries same-cycle WB address compares and write-data muxing even though most dynamic reads do not hit the current WB instruction.\\n\\nPrior resetless-regfile work showed the reset tree was not the interesting part of this block; the remaining structural target is the read/write bypass coupling itself. Moving the rare same-cycle WB dependency into the existing EX forwarding network should shorten the imem-data-to-ID/EX register-file read path without changing CoreMark CPI.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Make rtl/reg_file.sv a simple 2R1W architectural array: x0 remains hardwired to zero, writes remain synchronous, but read ports no longer mux in same-cycle w_data. Add a one-cycle registered WB-bypass source in core.sv that captures each real WB write, extend forward_unit.sv to select it as the...\n  Line 33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Wider resetless ifetch replay cache\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild the IF replay table as a 16-entry direct-mapped, valid-gated replay\\ncache indexed by pc[5:2]. Fill it only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, and\\non io_imemReady=0 hits keep supplying the cached instruction through the\\nexisting imem_effective_ready path. Do not add branch prediction metadata,\\ntarget repair state, or any EX feedback.\\n\\nMake the replay tag and instruction payload arrays reset...\n  Line 36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Warm replay during backend stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 8-entry IF replay table produced the largest recent improvement by\\nconverting random instruction-bus stalls into useful hot-loop instructions.\\nFollow-up attempts to widen or reset-retime the table regressed, which points\\naway from adding capacity on the fetch critical path and toward improving how\\noften the existing table is populated.\\n\\nBackend stalls from dmem backpressure, load-use bubbles, and iterative divide\\nalready stop decode from consuming the current fetch slot. Those cycles can be\\nused to issue harmless sequential instruction fetches and train the replay\\ntable, because instruction memory is immutable and wrong-path replay fills do\\nnot affect architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 8-entry IF replay table produced the largest recent improvement by\\nconverting random instruction-bus stalls into useful hot-loop instructions.\\nFollow-up attempts to widen or reset-retime the table regressed, which points\\naway from adding capacity on the fetch critical path and toward improving how\\noften the existing table is populated.\\n\\nBackend stalls from dmem backpressure, load-use bubbles, and iterative divide\\nalready stop decode from consuming the current fetch slot. Those cycles can be\\nused to issue harmless sequential instruction fetches and train the replay\\ntable, because instruction memory is immutable and wrong-path replay fills do\\nnot affect architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an opportunistic replay warmer inside IF. When the architectural PC is\\nheld for a non-redirect backend stall and the instruction bus is ready, drive\\nio_imemAddr from a small sequential prefetch cursor instead of the held PC and\\nfill the existing replay table with the returned instruction. Keep out.pc,\\nRVFI-visible instruction flow, redirect handling, and decode consumption tied\\nto the architectural PC; the wa...\n  Line 39: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r13s1\", \"title\": \"Register fetch-decode boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current bench core still has an unusually long frontend timing path: the IF\\nstage emits a combinational IF/ID payload, so io_imemData or replay-table data\\nflows through the fetch mux, decoder, immediate generator, register-file read\\naddresses, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Recent structural history\\nshows that adding predictors, queues, wider replay, and bypass paths usually\\nlost timing, while pruning existing stage plumbing helped. A minimal pipeline\\nboundary is therefore a better structural bet than adding more speculation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current bench core still has an unusually long frontend timing path: the IF\\nstage emits a combinational IF/ID payload, so io_imemData or replay-table data\\nflows through the fetch mux, decoder, immediate generator, register-file read\\naddresses, and into the ID/EX register in one cycle. Recent structural history\\nshows that adding predictors, queues, wider replay, and bypass paths usually\\nlost timing, while pruning existing stage plumbing helped. A minimal pipeline\\nboundary is therefore a better structural bet than adding more speculation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a real registered IF/ID boundary owned by the fetch stage, while keeping\\nthe existing 8-entry accepted-fetch replay table and NRET=1 retirement contract.\\nFetch should capture pc/instruction/valid only when the current fetch is usable\\nvia io_imemReady or a replay hit and ID can accept it; redirects flush the IF/ID\\nregister and update the PC to the resolved target. ID then decodes only the\\nregistered IF/ID payload, shortening the common FPGA path from instruction data\\nto decoded ID/EX controls and regfile source reads.\\n\\nThis will likely add one extra bubble on taken redirects compared with the\\ncurrent combinational IF/ID design, so the implementation should keep the\\nbranch/hazard machinery conservati...\n  Line 42: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r14s1\", \"title\": \"Valid-gated fetch bubbles\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffers, or wider replay state generally regressed because they put more muxing and control on already-sensitive paths. The successful changes instead pruned existing pipeline state or let the accepted-fetch replay table hide iStalls without branch-repair metadata.\\n\\nThe current frontend still forces every flush, redirect, or imem-miss bubble through a 32-bit NOP mux before decode. That mux sits directly on the imem/replay-data to decoder, immediate generator, regfile-address, and ID/EX capture path even though invalid instructions never retire.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffers, or wider replay state generally regressed because they put more muxing and control on already-sensitive paths. The successful changes instead pruned existing pipeline state or let the accepted-fetch replay table hide iStalls without branch-repair metadata.\\n\\nThe current frontend still forces every flush, redirect, or imem-miss bubble through a 32-bit NOP mux before decode. That mux sits directly on the imem/replay-data to decoder, immediate generator, regfile-address, and ID/EX capture path even though invalid instructions never retire.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Represent frontend bubbles with the existing valid bit instead of replacing the instruction word with ADDI x0,x0,0. IF should always pass the fetched or replayed instruction bits forward and set out.valid low for flush/redirect/imem-miss cycles. ID should zero side-effect controls and destination metadata whenever in.valid is low, and the load-use hazard should be gated by IF/ID and ID/EX validity so stale invalid instruction bits cannot create false interlocks.\\n\\nThis removes a normal-cycle 32-bit instruction mux from the fetch-to-decode cone and moves correctness onto compact valid/control gat...","metadata":{"matches":14,"truncated":false},"title":"category.*structural|structural","time":{"start":1778616530724,"end":1778616530741}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05c797344cc2adcf016a0388d27c48819b988853326b11616d"}},"id":"prt_e1dce7721001x9nUTRYVEySde6","sessionID":"ses_1e231c6a5ffeimPTYKeTd5e0wh","messageID":"msg_e1dce39a0001T76f4O65hpLin0"}}
