{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778616720817,"sessionID":"ses_1e231c6a5ffeimPTYKeTd5e0wh","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_nD5DrCSIOlxBK1QJJrK6DBwN","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r15s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-003-r15s2\n2: title: \"Victim-slot ifetch replay predictor\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   Branch-target predictors, RAS variants, countdown loop predictors, and\n6:   replay-table capacity/hash changes have mostly regressed because extra PC\n7:   muxing, EX repair metadata, or wider fetch routing cost more Fmax than they\n8:   recovered in CoreMark cycles. The one predictor that improved this core is\n9:   the accepted-fetch instruction replay table, which hides random hot-loop\n10:   instruction stalls without predicting control flow.\n11: \n12:   The remaining plausible replay weakness is direct-mapped thrashing between a\n13:   small number of hot PCs that share pc[4:2]. A single victim slot targets that\n14:   specific failure mode without widening the primary table or changing the\n15:   normal pc+4 fetch path.\n16: hypothesis: |\n17:   Keep the current 8-entry accepted-fetch replay predictor as the primary\n18:   lookup, but add one fully-tagged victim replay slot. When an accepted fetch\n19:   replaces a valid primary entry with a different tag, move the evicted tag and\n20:   instruction into the victim slot. On io_imemReady=0, first check the indexed\n21:   primary entry; if it misses, check the victim slot and replay its instruction\n22:   on a tag hit. Do not predict branches or jumps, do not add predicted-next-PC\n23:   metadata, and do not alter redirect handling.\n24: \n25:   This should recover iStall bubbles from two-way hot conflicts that the\n26:   direct-mapped replay table cannot hold, while adding only one extra tag\n27:   compare and one replay-data mux on the stalled-fetch path. It is narrower\n28:   than the failed 16-entry, folded-index, line-packed, or warm-prefetch replay\n29:   variants and preserves the immutable-instruction correctness argument.\n30: expected_impact:\n31:   fitness_delta_pct: 2\n32:   confidence: low\n33: changes:\n34:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n35:     description: \"Add a one-entry victim replay slot beside the existing 8-entry accepted-fetch table; fill it with evicted primary entries and consult it only on io_imemReady-low primary misses.\"\n\n(End of file - total 35 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-003-r15s2\ntitle: \"Victim-slot ifetch replay predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  Branch-target predictors, RAS variants, countdown loop predictors, and\n  replay-table capacity/hash changes have mostly regressed because extra PC\n  muxing, EX repair metadata, or wider fetch routing cost more Fmax than they\n  recovered in CoreMark cycles. The one predictor that improved this core is\n  the accepted-fetch instruction replay table, which hides random hot-loop\n  instruction stalls without predicting control flow.\n\n  The remaining plausible replay weakness is direct-mapped thrashing between a\n  small number of hot PCs that share pc[4:2]. A single victim slot targets that\n  specific failure mode without widening the primary table or changing the\n  normal pc+4 fetch path.\nhypothesis: |\n  Keep the current 8-entry accepted-fetch replay predictor as the primary\n  lookup, but add one fully-tagged victim replay slot. When an accepted fetch\n  replaces a valid primary entry with a different tag, move the evicted tag and\n  instruction into the victim slot. On io_imemReady=0, first check the indexed","truncated":false,"loaded":[]