{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778596475154,"sessionID":"ses_1e36402c1ffeWw0UF74O8zUKWR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Cju2AyYmNliu5wfNYw3lqL7v","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":1,"limit":10},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4c67411\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-12T14:04:33.574191Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative divider off ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with a small iterative divider/rem unit and\\nstall the single-issue pipeline while that unit is busy. Keep ADD/SUB/logic,\\nshifts, compares, address generation, branches, jumps, and all MUL/MULH\\nvariants single-cycle. This trades latency on rare divide instructions for a\\nshorter EX-stage combinational path and lower LUT pressure, which should raise\\nmedian Tang Nano 20K Fmax without materially changing CoreMark cycles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real combinational DIV/REM/% paths from the ALU while preserving ALTOPS behavior and single-cycle non-divide operations.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a sequential RV32M-correct divider/remainder unit covering signed, unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Start the divider for DIV/REM ops, hold the instruction until completion, and latch the final quotient or remainder into EX/MEM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an execute-busy stall input so IF... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple RV32M from EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static IF backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add IF-stage predecode for conditional branches and JAL. Predict JAL as taken, predict conditional branches as taken only when the B-immediate is negative, and otherwise predict fall-through. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX, then change EX redirect generation to redirect only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction. This should remove most loop-back branch bubbles in CoreMark with only modest mux/add/sign-extension logic in the fetch path and no stateful predictor tables.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can identify prediction mismatches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Predecode fetched JAL and backward conditional branch immediates, choose the predicted next PC, and emit prediction metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"descr... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 4 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"baseline-bench-4c67411\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-12T14:04:33.574191Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative divider off ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with a small iterative divider/rem unit and\\nstall the single-issue pipeline while that unit is busy. Keep ADD/SUB/logic,\\nshifts, compares, address generation, branches, jumps, and all MUL/MULH\\nvariants single-cycle. This trades latency on rare divide instructions for a\\nshorter EX-stage combinational path and lower LUT pressure, which should raise\\nmedian Tang Nano 20K Fmax without materially changing CoreMark cycles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real combinational DIV/REM/% paths from the ALU while preserving ALTOPS behavior and single-cycle non-divide operations.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a sequential RV32M-correct divider/remainder unit covering signed, unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Start the divider for DIV/REM ops, hold the instruction until completion, and latch the final quotient or remainder into EX/MEM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an execute-busy stall input so IF... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple RV32M from EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static IF backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add IF-stage predecode for conditional branches and JAL. Predict JAL as taken, predict conditional branches as taken only when the B-immediate is negative, and otherwise predict fall-through. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX, then change EX redirect generation to redirect only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction. This should remove most loop-back branch bubbles in CoreMark with only modest mux/add/sign-extension logic in the fetch path and no stateful predictor tables.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can identify prediction mismatches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Predecode fetched JAL and backward conditional branch immediates, choose the predicted next PC, and emit prediction metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"descr... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778596475140,"end":1778596475152}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_00b06e8c169b4dee016a033a7ac5c4819792068a044a934c8b"}},"id":"prt_e1c9c6ff40015n835rPhSbfvtK","sessionID":"ses_1e36402c1ffeWw0UF74O8zUKWR","messageID":"msg_e1c9c45ce001w5vMUShJRDJMXN"}}
