{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778596675889,"sessionID":"ses_1e36402c1ffeWw0UF74O8zUKWR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_LE797gG5alCsTlqme747mob8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n2: title: \"Share RV32M multiplier datapath\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   After moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU, the remaining RV32M\n6:   multiplier logic is a likely Fmax and routing limiter. The current ALU\n7:   computes signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned 64-bit\n8:   products in parallel even though each instruction consumes only one result.\n9: hypothesis: |\n10:   Replace the three parallel product nets with a single sign-controlled\n11:   extended multiply selected from the ALU_MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU operation.\n12:   MUL can still use the low 32 bits, while the high-half variants select the\n13:   correct signedness through operand extension. This should reduce LUT/DSP\n14:   duplication and the ALU result-mux/routing cone without changing pipeline\n15:   latency, CoreMark instruction count, RVFI behavior, or ALTOPS semantics.\n16: expected_impact:\n17:   fitness_delta_pct: 5\n18:   confidence: medium\n19: changes:\n20:   - file: rtl/alu.sv\n21:     description: \"Collapse the three RV32M multiply products into one sign-selected extended product while preserving ALTOPS substitutions and single-cycle MUL latency.\"\n22:   - file: test/test_alu.py\n23:     description: \"Keep or extend MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors to guard signedness correctness after sharing the multiplier datapath.\"\n\n(End of file - total 23 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\ntitle: \"Share RV32M multiplier datapath\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  After moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU, the remaining RV32M\n  multiplier logic is a likely Fmax and routing limiter. The current ALU\n  computes signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned 64-bit\n  products in parallel even though each instruction consumes only one result.\nhypothesis: |\n  Replace the three parallel product nets with a single sign-controlled\n  extended multiply selected from the ALU_MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU operation.\n  MUL can still use the low 32 bits, while the high-half variants select the\n  correct signedness through operand extension. This should reduce LUT/DSP\n  duplication and the ALU result-mux/routing cone without changing pipeline\n  latency, CoreMark instruction count, RVFI behavior, or ALTOPS semantics.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/alu.sv","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778596675878,"end":1778596675887}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05cbda58bc0f4c0a016a033b43be3081949a32173f720749d7"}},"id":"prt_e1c9f8101001QfCJambiTrEu39","sessionID":"ses_1e36402c1ffeWw0UF74O8zUKWR","messageID":"msg_e1c9f5397001Y06Ycy8zHGzShP"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778596675889,"sessionID":"ses_1e36402c1ffeWw0UF74O8zUKWR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_iWyN0oaBrfBHNbRDo451fENl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\n2: title: \"PC-indexed BTB predictor\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The previous static predictor recovered some loop-control bubbles but put\n6:   instruction predecode and immediate generation on the fetch next-PC path,\n7:   which is risky for Tang Nano 20K Fmax. CoreMark still has repeated taken\n8:   loop branches and some direct/indirect jumps, so a predictor can help if the\n9:   lookup path is driven only by the registered fetch PC rather than by\n10:   io_imemData.\n11: hypothesis: |\n12:   Add a small direct-mapped PC-indexed BTB with a 2-bit taken counter and target\n13:   per entry. IF predicts taken only on a tag hit with a taken counter and uses\n14:   the stored target; otherwise it fetches pc+4. EX resolves the actual next PC,\n15:   updates the table for branches and jumps, and redirects only when the resolved\n16:   next PC differs from the carried prediction.\n17: \n18:   This should recover most steady-state CoreMark loop-back bubbles after warmup\n19:   without the failed imem_data predecode critical path. The cost is a small\n20:   PC-indexed LUT/register table and a compare/mux in IF, so the expected gain is\n21:   modest but more Fmax-safe than static fetch predecode.\n22: expected_impact:\n23:   fitness_delta_pct: 5\n24:   confidence: medium\n25: changes:\n26:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n27:     description: \"Carry predicted next-PC metadata from IF through ID/EX so EX can detect prediction mismatches without changing the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\"\n28:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n29:     description: \"Add a small PC-indexed BTB/BHT lookup and update interface, selecting either the stored predicted target or pc+4 without decoding io_imemData.\"\n30:   - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n31:     description: \"Latch IF prediction metadata into the ID/EX bundle alongside the decoded instruction.\"\n32:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n33:     description: \"Resolve the actual next PC, generate predictor update information, and redirect only when the actual next PC mismatches the carried prediction.\"\n34:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n35:     description: \"Wire predictor update signals between EX and IF while preserving the existing single-retirement RVFI port shape.\"\n\n(End of file - total 35 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\ntitle: \"PC-indexed BTB predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The previous static predictor recovered some loop-control bubbles but put\n  instruction predecode and immediate generation on the fetch next-PC path,\n  which is risky for Tang Nano 20K Fmax. CoreMark still has repeated taken\n  loop branches and some direct/indirect jumps, so a predictor can help if the\n  lookup path is driven only by the registered fetch PC rather than by\n  io_imemData.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a small direct-mapped PC-indexed BTB with a 2-bit taken counter and target\n  per entry. IF predicts taken only on a tag hit with a taken counter and uses\n  the stored target; otherwise it fetches pc+4. EX resolves the actual next PC,\n  updates the table for branches and jumps, and redirects only when the resolved\n  next PC differs from the carried prediction.\n\n  This should recover most steady-state CoreMark loop-back bubbles after warmup\n  without the failed imem_data predecode critical path. The cost is a small\n  PC-indexed LUT/register table and a compare/mux in IF, so the expected gain is","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r2s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778596675880,"end":1778596675888}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_05cbda58bc0f4c0a016a033b43be408194b1ff3bb8a4c11209"}},"id":"prt_e1c9f8127001G3tGyQhmdlBnN5","sessionID":"ses_1e36402c1ffeWw0UF74O8zUKWR","messageID":"msg_e1c9f5397001Y06Ycy8zHGzShP"}}
