32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static IF backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add IF-stage predecode for conditional branches and JAL. Predict JAL as taken, predict conditional branches as taken only