{"type":"text","timestamp":1778602352964,"sessionID":"ses_1e30c49b6ffe3HngQXbTssxUx1","part":{"id":"prt_e1cf5f77a0010deMuE2qv4Gnxs","messageID":"msg_e1cf40912001W75iVp0y8oqGz4","sessionID":"ses_1e30c49b6ffe3HngQXbTssxUx1","type":"text","text":"Structural history shows fetch queues, store buffers, and predictor plumbing all regressed from added control-path complexity. The unmeasured gap is a cleaner structural retime of the multiply path: prior high-half attempts kept low-half MUL on the common EX cone, so they never removed the likely remaining wide arithmetic limiter.","time":{"start":1778602342266,"end":1778602352963},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_005cf8e72f26605a016a0351662314819682bd89b39dbb82ed","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778602353014,"sessionID":"ses_1e30c49b6ffe3HngQXbTssxUx1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cPwJwypheARenXRIOtQOLe1V","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":3,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple RV32M from EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 3-3 of 13. Use offset=4 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple RV32M from EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778602353006,"end":1778602353013}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_005cf8e72f26605a016a035170d43081968df9ee429b1f1c49"}},"id":"prt_e1cf62153001UDHcLeE6AUKH9g","sessionID":"ses_1e30c49b6ffe3HngQXbTssxUx1","messageID":"msg_e1cf40912001W75iVp0y8oqGz4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778602353032,"sessionID":"ses_1e30c49b6ffe3HngQXbTssxUx1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cryWawtWxiJljvjc72iRcI7V","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":6,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple fetch with skid queue\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a small two-entry instruction skid/prefetch queue between the fetch PC\\nand ID. The fetch side advances and enqueues whenever io_imemReady is high and\\nthe queue is not full; the decode side consumes only when the existing backend\\nhazard logic allows ID to advance. Redirects flush the queue and restart fetch\\nat the resolved target, preserving precise RVFI retirement and the NRET=1 port\\ncontract.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should hide a fraction of random iStall cycles\\nbehind dmem stalls, load-use bubbles, and divide busy cycles, while adding only\\na shallow FIFO and PC muxes instead of putting branch predecode on the\\nimem_data-to-next_pc critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single PC-to-ID combinational fetch path with ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 6-6 of 13. Use offset=7 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple fetch with skid queue\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a small two-entry instruction skid/prefetch queue between the fetch PC\\nand ID. The fetch side advances and enqueues whenever io_imemReady is high and\\nthe queue is not full; the decode side consumes only when the existing backend\\nhazard logic allows ID to advance. Redirects flush the queue and restart fetch\\nat the resolved target, preserving precise RVFI retirement and the NRET=1 port\\ncontract.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should hide a fraction of random iStall cycles\\nbehind dmem stalls, load-use bubbles, and divide busy cycles, while adding only\\na shallow FIFO and PC muxes instead of putting branch predecode on the\\nimem_data-to-next_pc critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single PC-to-ID combinational fetch path with ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778602353026,"end":1778602353031}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_005cf8e72f26605a016a035170d44081969147756c4767a3b2"}},"id":"prt_e1cf62170001kRBGloSEaetNph","sessionID":"ses_1e30c49b6ffe3HngQXbTssxUx1","messageID":"msg_e1cf40912001W75iVp0y8oqGz4"}}
