{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778604275150,"sessionID":"ses_1e2f21bafffeKkj6hCAvSN3gsH","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_1T16fyQyb4ZK4HcMtBDdJqSl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Resetless LUTRAM register file\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\n+\n+  Retargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rebuild rtl/reg_file.sv as resetless storage for x1-x31, with x0 represented only by constant-zero read behavior and dropped writes. Preserve the same two asynchronous read ports, one synchronous write port, and same-cycle write-first bypass, but remove the per-bit synchronous reset from the data array.\n+\n+  Use deterministic power-up initialization if needed for simulation/FPGA startup, but do not clear the data array through reset. This should let Yosys map the register file to distributed RAM or at least smaller unreset storage, cutting reset/write mux depth and routing pressure without adding any new frontend, backend, or M-extension control state.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Restructure the integer register file as resetless x1-x31 storage, keep x0 as constant-zero behavior, and preserve write-first bypass semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r6s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\n+title: \"Resetless LUTRAM register file\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\n+\n+  Retargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Rebuild rtl/reg_file.sv as resetless storage for x1-x31, with x0 represented only by constant-zero read behavior and dropped writes. Preserve the same two asynchronous read ports, one synchronous write port, and same-cycle write-first bypass, but remove the per-bit synchronous reset from the data array.\n+\n+  Use deterministic power-up initialization if needed for simulation/FPGA startup, but do not clear the data array through reset. This should let Yosys map the register file to distributed RAM or at least smaller un