{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778605221569,"sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_pcedppXhA3hEpJH23n0kogmC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"\"category\": \"structural\"|category: structural|structural","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 6 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple RV32M from EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple fetch with skid queue\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a small two-entry instruction skid/prefetch queue between the fetch PC\\nand ID. The fetch side advances and enqueues whenever io_imemReady is high and\\nthe queue is not full; the decode side consumes only when the existing backend\\nhazard logic allows ID to advance. Redirects flush the queue and restart fetch\\nat the resolved target, preserving precise RVFI retirement and the NRET=1 port\\ncontract.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should hide a fraction of random iStall cycles\\nbehind dmem stalls, load-use bubbles, and divide busy cycles, while adding only\\na shallow FIFO and PC muxes instead of putting branch predecode on the\\nimem_data-to-next_pc critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single PC-to-ID combinational fetch path with ...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"One-entry RAM store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current in-order pipeline freezes behind every STORE whenever io_dmemReady\\nis low, even though most stores do not produce a value needed by the following\\ninstruction. In the tournament cosim mode dmem sees random backpressure, so\\nCoreMark pays avoidable full-pipeline bubbles on ordinary RAM stores.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts put new logic on the fetch path or tried to decouple\\nthe whole M-extension unit. A narrower backend store buffer should attack a\\ncommon stall source while leaving fetch, branch resolution, RVFI width, and the\\nworking iterative divider structure unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current in-order pipeline freezes behind every STORE whenever io_dmemReady\\nis low, even though most stores do not produce a value needed by the following\\ninstruction. In the tournament cosim mode dmem sees random backpressure, so\\nCoreMark pays avoidable full-pipeline bubbles on ordinary RAM stores.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts put new logic on the fetch path or tried to decouple\\nthe whole M-extension unit. A narrower backend store buffer should attack a\\ncommon stall source while leaving fetch, branch resolution, RVFI width, and the\\nworking iterative divider structure unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry write buffer for aligned, non-MMIO RAM stores. When a store\\nreaches MEM and the dmem bus is not ready, capture its address, byte mask, and\\nreplicated write data into the buffer, retire the store once architecturally\\nenqueued, and let younger non-memory instructions continue. Drain the buffer\\nto dmem as soon as io_dmemReady returns.\\n\\nPreserve ordering by stalling any younger load/store while the buffer is full\\nunless the pending store has drained, and keep UART/timing-marker MMIO stores\\nunbuffered so CoreMark brackets and output timing remain tied to real bus\\nacceptance. This should hide a fraction of random dmem ...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Split high-half multiplier\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a simple single-cycle low-32-bit product, because that is the\\nmultiply form most likely used by compiled CoreMark matrix code. Move only\\nMULH, MULHU, and MULHSU into a small iterative high-half multiply unit with\\nthe same start/done/ack discipline already proven necessary for the divider.\\n\\nIn the core build, EX should treat the high-half multiply variants like the\\nexisting iterative divider: hold ID/EX while the unit runs, latch the original\\nforwarded operands for RVFI, and emit exactly one EX/MEM res...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Pipelined full multiplier unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best measured improvement came from removing cold divide/remainder logic from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path. The remaining wide arithmetic limiter is the\\nsingle-cycle RV32M multiplier cone: the ALU still builds multiple 64-bit products\\nin the same result path used by ordinary adds, branches, address generation, and\\nstores. Prior high-half-only attempts regressed because low-half MUL stayed in\\nthat common cone, so the critical path was not structurally removed.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best measured improvement came from removing cold divide/remainder logic from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path. The remaining wide arithmetic limiter is the\\nsingle-cycle RV32M multiplier cone: the ALU still builds multiple 64-bit products\\nin the same result path used by ordinary adds, branches, address generation, and\\nstores. Prior high-half-only attempts regressed because low-half MUL stayed in\\nthat common cone, so the critical path was not structurally removed.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move all real MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU execution out of rtl/alu.sv into a dedicated\\ntwo-cycle multiplier unit built from registered 16x16 partial products followed\\nby a registered combine/sign-select stage. EX should treat every real multiply\\nlike the existing iterative divider: latch the forwarded operands, assert a\\nbusy stall while the unit is active, and emit exactly one EX/MEM result with the\\noriginal operands preserved for RVFI.\\n\\nThis pays one extra cycle on CoreMark multiply instructions, but it removes the\\n32x32/64-bit product cone from the common single-cycle RV32I execute path and\\nshould improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax more than the modest MUL CPI loss. Under\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the existing algebraic substitutions single-cycle so\\nthe formal harness remains tractable and consistent with the spec files.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\"...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Resetless LUTRAM register file\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\\n\\nRetargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\\n\\nRetargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild rtl/reg_file.sv as resetless storage for x1-x31, with x0 represented only by constant-zero read behavior and dropped writes. Preserve the same two asynchronous read ports, one synchronous write port, and same-cycle write-first bypass, but remove the per-bit synchronous reset from the data array.\\n\\nUse deterministic power-up initialization if needed for simulation/FPGA startup, but do not clear the data array through reset. This should let Yosys map the register file to distributed RAM or at least smaller unreset storage, cutting reset/write mux depth and routing...","metadata":{"matches":6,"truncated":false},"title":"\"category\": \"structural\"|category: structural|structural","time":{"start":1778605221560,"end":1778605221569}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_030e19d6f6d8ccf2016a035ca570688190b9ad442d69ce7c04"}},"id":"prt_e1d21e6b6001EKV9V5uB4Sli7V","sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","messageID":"msg_e1d217b6d001sQ5iUhJ5MIZ16O"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778605221571,"sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_sUNodDf6sjR8VFWY7uVMuBKX","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"pipeline|stage|fanout|flop|control|forward|hazard|retire|MEM/WB|EX/MEM","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 18 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative divider off ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with a small iterative divider/rem unit and\\nstall the single-issue pipeline while that unit is busy. Keep ADD/SUB/logic,\\nshifts, compares, address generation, branches, jumps, and all MUL/MULH\\nvariants single-cycle. This trades latency on rare divide instructions for a\\nshorter EX-stage combinational path and lower LUT pressure, which should raise\\nmedian Tang Nano 20K Fmax without materially changing CoreMark cycles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real combinational DIV/REM/% paths from the ALU while preserving ALTOPS behavior and single-cycle non-divide operations.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a sequential RV32M-correct divider/remainder unit covering signed, unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Start the divider for DIV/REM ops, hold the instruction until completion, and latch the final quotient or remainder into EX/MEM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an execute-busy stall input so IF...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple RV32M from EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static IF backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add IF-stage predecode for conditional branches and JAL. Predict JAL as taken, predict conditional branches as taken only when the B-immediate is negative, and otherwise predict fall-through. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX, then change EX redirect generation to redirect only when the resolved next PC differs from the prediction. This should remove most loop-back branch bubbles in CoreMark with only modest mux/add/sign-extension logic in the fetch path and no stateful predictor tables.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can identify prediction mismatches.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Predecode fetched JAL and backward conditional branch immediates, choose the predicted next PC, and emit prediction metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"descr...\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Share RV32M multiplier datapath\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"After moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU, the remaining RV32M\\nmultiplier logic is a likely Fmax and routing limiter. The current ALU\\ncomputes signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned 64-bit\\nproducts in parallel even though each instruction consumes only one result.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"After moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU, the remaining RV32M\\nmultiplier logic is a likely Fmax and routing limiter. The current ALU\\ncomputes signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and signed*unsigned 64-bit\\nproducts in parallel even though each instruction consumes only one result.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three parallel product nets with a single sign-controlled\\nextended multiply selected from the ALU_MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU operation.\\nMUL can still use the low 32 bits, while the high-half variants select the\\ncorrect signedness through operand extension. This should reduce LUT/DSP\\nduplication and the ALU result-mux/routing cone without changing pipeline\\nlatency, CoreMark instruction count, RVFI behavior, or ALTOPS semantics.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Collapse the three RV32M multiply products into one sign-selected extended product while preserving ALTOPS substitutions and single-cycle MUL latency.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Keep or extend MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge-case vectors to guard signedness correctness after sharing the multiplier datapath.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Collapse the three RV32M multiply products into one sign-selected extended product while preserving ALTOPS substitutions and single-cycle MUL latency.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Keep or extend MULH/MULHU/MULHSU edge...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple fetch with skid queue\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current frontend treats every low io_imemReady cycle as an immediate\\ndecode bubble, and backend stalls hold the PC so the core cannot fetch ahead\\nwhile memory, load-use, or iterative divide latency is already stopping\\nretirement. In the tournament cosim mode both instruction and data buses see\\nrandom stalls, so overlapping independent frontend availability with backend\\nstalls can improve CoreMark cycles without relying on the failed IF-stage\\ninstruction predecode path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Insert a small two-entry instruction skid/prefetch queue between the fetch PC\\nand ID. The fetch side advances and enqueues whenever io_imemReady is high and\\nthe queue is not full; the decode side consumes only when the existing backend\\nhazard logic allows ID to advance. Redirects flush the queue and restart fetch\\nat the resolved target, preserving precise RVFI retirement and the NRET=1 port\\ncontract.\\n\\nThis structural decoupling should hide a fraction of random iStall cycles\\nbehind dmem stalls, load-use bubbles, and divide busy cycles, while adding only\\na shallow FIFO and PC muxes instead of putting branch predecode on the\\nimem_data-to-next_pc critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single PC-to-ID combinational fetch path with ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"PC-indexed BTB predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The previous static predictor recovered some loop-control bubbles but put\\ninstruction predecode and immediate generation on the fetch next-PC path,\\nwhich is risky for Tang Nano 20K Fmax. CoreMark still has repeated taken\\nloop branches and some direct/indirect jumps, so a predictor can help if the\\nlookup path is driven only by the registered fetch PC rather than by\\nio_imemData.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The previous static predictor recovered some loop-control bubbles but put\\ninstruction predecode and immediate generation on the fetch next-PC path,\\nwhich is risky for Tang Nano 20K Fmax. CoreMark still has repeated taken\\nloop branches and some direct/indirect jumps, so a predictor can help if the\\nlookup path is driven only by the registered fetch PC rather than by\\nio_imemData.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped PC-indexed BTB with a 2-bit taken counter and target\\nper entry. IF predicts taken only on a tag hit with a taken counter and uses\\nthe stored target; otherwise it fetches pc+4. EX resolves the actual next PC,\\nupdates the table for branches and jumps, and redirects only when the resolved\\nnext PC differs from the carried prediction.\\n\\nThis should recover most steady-state CoreMark loop-back bubbles after warmup\\nwithout the failed imem_data predecode critical path. The cost is a small\\nPC-indexed LUT/register table and a compare/mux in IF, so the expected gain is\\nmodest but more Fmax-safe than static fetch predecode.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Carry predicted next-PC metadata from IF through ID/EX so EX can detect prediction mismatches without changing the NRET=1 RVFI contract.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a small PC-indexed BTB/BHT lookup and update interface, selecting either the stored predicted tar...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Late load-store data bypass\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector stalls whenever a load in EX has an rd\\nmatching either raw source field of the following IF/ID instruction. That is\\nnecessary for ALU operands, branch compares, and store address bases, but it\\nis over-conservative for a STORE whose rs2 data is not consumed until MEM.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels perform many load/store moves and immediate-form\\noperations, so avoidable one-cycle bubbles directly reduce iterations per\\ncycle without helping correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use detector stalls whenever a load in EX has an rd\\nmatching either raw source field of the following IF/ID instruction. That is\\nnecessary for ALU operands, branch compares, and store address bases, but it\\nis over-conservative for a STORE whose rs2 data is not consumed until MEM.\\nCoreMark's timed kernels perform many load/store moves and immediate-form\\noperations, so avoidable one-cycle bubbles directly reduce iterations per\\ncycle without helping correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Refine the load-use hazard to distinguish operands needed in EX from store\\ndata that can be supplied one stage later. For a following STORE, keep the\\nstall only when the load feeds rs1, the address base; allow an rs2-only\\ndependency to advance and resolve it with a MEM-stage bypass from the current\\nMEM/WB result into the store-data path. The bypass must also update the\\nretiring store's RVFI rs2_rdata and mem_wdata fields so formal/cosim observe\\nthe architectural source value.\\n\\nDefault unknown or illegal encodings to conservative source use in the\\nhazard predecode, preserving trap and RVFI behavior. This should recover IPC\\nfrom load-to-store and false rs2-immediate hazards while adding only a small\\nMEM data mux, avoiding the fetch critical-path costs seen in prior predictor\\nattempts and the EX multiplier regressions from prior micro-opts....\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"One-entry RAM store buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current in-order pipeline freezes behind every STORE whenever io_dmemReady\\nis low, even though most stores do not produce a value needed by the following\\ninstruction. In the tournament cosim mode dmem sees random backpressure, so\\nCoreMark pays avoidable full-pipeline bubbles on ordinary RAM stores.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts put new logic on the fetch path or tried to decouple\\nthe whole M-extension unit. A narrower backend store buffer should attack a\\ncommon stall source while leaving fetch, branch resolution, RVFI width, and the\\nworking iterative divider structure unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current in-order pipeline freezes behind every STORE whenever io_dmemReady\\nis low, even though most stores do not produce a value needed by the following\\ninstruction. In the tournament cosim mode dmem sees random backpressure, so\\nCoreMark pays avoidable full-pipeline bubbles on ordinary RAM stores.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts put new logic on the fetch path or tried to decouple\\nthe whole M-extension unit. A narrower backend store buffer should attack a\\ncommon stall source while leaving fetch, branch resolution, RVFI width, and the\\nworking iterative divider structure unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry write buffer for aligned, non-MMIO RAM stores. When a store\\nreaches MEM and the dmem bus is not ready, capture its address, byte mask, and\\nreplicated write data into the buffer, retire the store once architecturally\\nenqueued, and let younger non-memory instructions continue. Drain the buffer\\nto dmem as soon as io_dmemReady returns.\\n\\nPreserve ordering by stalling any younger load/store while the buffer is full\\nunless the pending store has drained, and keep UART/timing-marker MMIO stores\\nunbuffered so CoreMark brackets and output timing remain tied to real bus\\nacceptance. This should hide a fraction of random dmem ...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"One-entry hot redirect predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The previous predictor attempts show that CoreMark has exploitable taken loop\\ncontrol flow, but larger or instruction-predecode-based predictors hurt the\\nTang Nano 20K fetch critical path enough to erase the cycle savings. The most\\npromising remaining predictor angle is to keep the frontend prediction logic\\ndeliberately tiny and only target the hottest repeated redirect.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The previous predictor attempts show that CoreMark has exploitable taken loop\\ncontrol flow, but larger or instruction-predecode-based predictors hurt the\\nTang Nano 20K fetch critical path enough to erase the cycle savings. The most\\npromising remaining predictor angle is to keep the frontend prediction logic\\ndeliberately tiny and only target the hottest repeated redirect.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry tagged redirect cache in IF. On an exact fetch-PC tag hit,\\npredict the cached target as the next PC; otherwise fetch pc+4. EX carries the\\npredicted-next metadata, resolves the actual next PC for every retiring\\ninstruction, redirects only on a prediction mismatch, updates the entry on\\ntaken branches and jumps, and invalidates it when the same PC resolves not\\ntaken or non-control.\\n\\nThis recovers steady-state bubbles for one dominant CoreMark loop backedge or\\nrepeated jump while avoiding the failed imem_data predecode path and avoiding\\na multi-entry BTB/BHT table. The hardware cost should be one valid bit, one\\nPC tag compare, one target register, and a next-PC mux, so the Fmax risk is\\nmuch lower than the prior predictor designs.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC and predicted-taken metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate the one-entry prediction precisely.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\":...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative high-half multiply\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The successful divider change showed that removing rare RV32M operations from\\nthe common EX-stage combinational cone can raise FPGA Fmax without materially\\nhurting CoreMark cycles. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply\\nproducts in parallel for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU, even though CoreMark's\\ntimed hot path is expected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than\\nhigh-half multiply variants.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The successful divider change showed that removing rare RV32M operations from\\nthe common EX-stage combinational cone can raise FPGA Fmax without materially\\nhurting CoreMark cycles. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply\\nproducts in parallel for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and MULHSU, even though CoreMark's\\ntimed hot path is expected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than\\nhigh-half multiply variants.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a single-cycle low-half multiply, but move MULH, MULHU, and\\nMULHSU onto a small iterative high-half multiplier that reuses the existing\\nexecute-busy stall pattern. This should let synthesis reduce the common ALU\\nmultiplier to only the low 32 result bits for MUL, while removing the signed\\nand signed/unsigned high-product cones from the normal ADD/branch/load/store\\nexecute path.\\n\\nUnlike the prior shared 33x33 multiplier attempt, this does not add a wider\\nsignedness mux to every multiply operation. The latency penalty is paid only\\nfor high-half M-extension instructions, which should be rare or absent in the\\nCoreMark timed region, while RV32M correctness remains covered by dedicated\\nunit tests and cosim.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real MULH/MULHU/MULHSU product generation from the common ALU path while preserving ALTOPS substitutions and single-cycle ...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Split high-half multiplier\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a simple single-cycle low-32-bit product, because that is the\\nmultiply form most likely used by compiled CoreMark matrix code. Move only\\nMULH, MULHU, and MULHSU into a small iterative high-half multiply unit with\\nthe same start/done/ack discipline already proven necessary for the divider.\\n\\nIn the core build, EX should treat the high-half multiply variants like the\\nexisting iterative divider: hold ID/EX while the unit runs, latch the original\\nforwarded operands for RVFI, and emit exactly one EX/MEM res...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Return-address stack predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core regressed because they put too much\\ntarget-generation or tag-lookup logic on the shallow fetch critical path.\\nCoreMark still contains repeated call/return control flow in addition to\\nloops, and returns are the one dynamic-control case where a tiny predictor\\ncan provide a target without a BTB target array or branch-immediate adder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core regressed because they put too much\\ntarget-generation or tag-lookup logic on the shallow fetch critical path.\\nCoreMark still contains repeated call/return control flow in addition to\\nloops, and returns are the one dynamic-control case where a tiny predictor\\ncan provide a target without a BTB target array or branch-immediate adder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small return-address stack for JALR return prediction only. Push\\npc+4 when a legal link-register JAL/JALR call resolves, pop when a legal\\nreturn resolves, and in IF predict a fetched `jalr x0, x1/x5, 0` to the\\ncurrent stack top. Carry predicted-next-PC metadata to EX so a correctly\\npredicted return does not flush, while any mismatch redirects and repairs\\nthe stack precisely.\\n\\nThis intentionally does not predict conditional branches and does not add\\na PC-indexed BTB/tag compare. The IF critical-path addition should be only\\na narrow opcode/rd/rs1/imm-zero return recognizer plus a mux to the stack\\ntop, so Fmax risk is lower than the failed static branch, BTB, and hot\\nredirect predictor variants. The cycle gain is expected to be modest but\\npositive if CoreMark's timed call/return traffic is frequent enough.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC and return-predicted metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles for precise EX validation.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Case-decoded load byte lanes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest prior result came from shortening a real timing cone without\\nadding new frontend or memory-ordering state. Recent predictor, store-buffer,\\nand multiplier refinements all regressed because extra muxing and control\\npressure outweighed any cycle savings. The MEM stage still contains dynamic\\nbyte-lane shifts on the load/store path, including a variable right shift by\\naddr[1:0] * 8, which can synthesize into a wider mux cone on the BRAM-read to\\nMEM/WB path used heavily by CoreMark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest prior result came from shortening a real timing cone without\\nadding new frontend or memory-ordering state. Recent predictor, store-buffer,\\nand multiplier refinements all regressed because extra muxing and control\\npressure outweighed any cycle savings. The MEM stage still contains dynamic\\nbyte-lane shifts on the load/store path, including a variable right shift by\\naddr[1:0] * 8, which can synthesize into a wider mux cone on the BRAM-read to\\nMEM/WB path used heavily by CoreMark.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rewrite the MEM-stage byte/halfword load extraction and byte-mask generation\\nas explicit small case trees on alu_result[1:0] and mem_width. This removes\\nthe variable shift and shift-amount multiply from the common load path while\\npreserving the existing dmem port contract, misalignment trap gating, RVFI\\nALIGNED_MEM reporting, and single-cycle MEM latency. IPC should be unchanged,\\nbut LUT depth and routing on the load-data and store-mask cones should drop\\nenough to modestly improve median Tang Nano 20K Fmax.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace dynamic byte-lane shifts and masks with explicit case-based byte/halfword selectors while preserving misalignment, dmem, and RVFI behavior.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Pipelined full multiplier unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best measured improvement came from removing cold divide/remainder logic from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path. The remaining wide arithmetic limiter is the\\nsingle-cycle RV32M multiplier cone: the ALU still builds multiple 64-bit products\\nin the same result path used by ordinary adds, branches, address generation, and\\nstores. Prior high-half-only attempts regressed because low-half MUL stayed in\\nthat common cone, so the critical path was not structurally removed.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best measured improvement came from removing cold divide/remainder logic from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path. The remaining wide arithmetic limiter is the\\nsingle-cycle RV32M multiplier cone: the ALU still builds multiple 64-bit products\\nin the same result path used by ordinary adds, branches, address generation, and\\nstores. Prior high-half-only attempts regressed because low-half MUL stayed in\\nthat common cone, so the critical path was not structurally removed.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move all real MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU execution out of rtl/alu.sv into a dedicated\\ntwo-cycle multiplier unit built from registered 16x16 partial products followed\\nby a registered combine/sign-select stage. EX should treat every real multiply\\nlike the existing iterative divider: latch the forwarded operands, assert a\\nbusy stall while the unit is active, and emit exactly one EX/MEM result with the\\noriginal operands preserved for RVFI.\\n\\nThis pays one extra cycle on CoreMark multiply instructions, but it removes the\\n32x32/64-bit product cone from the common single-cycle RV32I execute path and\\nshould improve Tang Nano 20K Fmax more than the modest MUL CPI loss. Under\\nRISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the existing algebraic substitutions single-cycle so\\nthe formal harness remains tractable and consistent with the spec files.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\"...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Low-bit loop backedge predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core regressed because full IF predecode,\\nBTB tag/target lookup, hot redirect caching, and return prediction all added\\ntoo much logic to the shallow fetch next-PC path. CoreMark still has repeated\\ncounted-loop backedges, but the predictor must be narrower than those failed\\ndesigns to have any chance of improving fitness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts on this core regressed because full IF predecode,\\nBTB tag/target lookup, hot redirect caching, and return prediction all added\\ntoo much logic to the shallow fetch next-PC path. CoreMark still has repeated\\ncounted-loop backedges, but the predictor must be narrower than those failed\\ndesigns to have any chance of improving fitness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry conditional-loop backedge predictor that learns only a hot\\ntaken backward conditional branch at EX and predicts it in IF using a small\\nlow-bit PC match, for example pc[7:2], plus a stored target. Do not predict\\nJAL, JALR, forward branches, or returns, and do not keep a full tag, table,\\nor saturating counters. Carry predicted next-PC metadata with the instruction\\nso EX redirects only on mismatch and updates or clears the entry from the\\nresolved branch.\\n\\nThis intentionally accepts occasional low-bit alias mispredictions because\\nthey are corrected precisely at EX, while making the IF critical-path addition\\nmuch smaller than the previous predictor designs. If CoreMark has one dominant\\ninner-loop backedge, the cycle savings may outweigh the small compare and mux;\\nif aliasing or routing dominates, the hypothesis should fail cleanly without\\nweakening RVFI or trap invariants.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted next-PC and predicted-valid fields to IF/ID and ID/EX bund...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Prune dead pipeline control bits\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent bench attempts regressed when they added new muxing or control to the\\nalready-shallow pipeline. The current RTL still carries several EX-only or\\nunused control/state fields through later pipeline registers, including the\\nredundant LUI control bit and unused branch metadata after EX has already\\nresolved the redirect. Those flops and nets do not improve IPC, but they can\\nadd routing pressure and fanout on the FPGA implementation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent bench attempts regressed when they added new muxing or control to the\\nalready-shallow pipeline. The current RTL still carries several EX-only or\\nunused control/state fields through later pipeline registers, including the\\nredundant LUI control bit and unused branch metadata after EX has already\\nresolved the redirect. Those flops and nets do not improve IPC, but they can\\nadd routing pressure and fanout on the FPGA implementation.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Narrow the control/state carried past each stage to only what the next stages\\nactually consume. Remove the unused is_lui control bit because LUI is already\\nrepresented by ALU_LUI plus alu_src, stop storing branch_taken/branch_target\\nin EX/MEM after redirect resolution, and explicitly avoid propagating EX-only\\ndecode controls into MEM/WB. This should reduce register count, fanout, and\\nlate-stage routing without changing retirement timing, RVFI contents, trap\\nbehavior, memory ordering, or CoreMark cycle count.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove unused pipeline-bundle fields and narrow late-stage control state to the bits consumed after EX.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/decoder.sv\", \"description\": \"Drop the redundant is_lui output while preserving ALU_LUI decode and illegal-instruction defaults.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\"...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"Resetless LUTRAM register file\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\\n\\nRetargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior structural attempts that added frontend predictors, fetch queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiplier control lost more Fmax than they recovered in CoreMark cycles. The remaining low-risk structural target is the integer register file: it is currently a resettable 32x32 flop bank even though only x0 has architectural zero behavior, and the full synchronous reset adds muxing and routing to every stored bit.\\n\\nRetargeting this storage without changing pipeline timing should improve FPGA placement/routing pressure while preserving the existing single-issue CPI, hazard behavior, forwarding, and RVFI contract.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild rtl/reg_file.sv as resetless storage for x1-x31, with x0 represented only by constant-zero read behavior and dropped writes. Preserve the same two asynchronous read ports, one synchronous write port, and same-cycle write-first bypass, but remove the per-bit synchronous reset from the data array.\\n\\nUse deterministic power-up initialization if needed for simulation/FPGA startup, but do not clear the data array through reset. This should let Yosys map the register file to distributed RAM or at least smaller unreset storage, cutting reset/write mux depth and routing...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Countdown loop predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts recovered plausible branch bubbles but regressed because\\nthey put instruction predecode, PC tag compares, target-table lookup, or return\\ndecode directly on the shallow fetch next-PC path. CoreMark still has repeated\\ncounted-loop backedges, so the remaining promising predictor angle is one that\\navoids both imem_data decode and PC-indexed table lookup during fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts recovered plausible branch bubbles but regressed because\\nthey put instruction predecode, PC tag compares, target-table lookup, or return\\ndecode directly on the shallow fetch next-PC path. CoreMark still has repeated\\ncounted-loop backedges, so the remaining promising predictor angle is one that\\navoids both imem_data decode and PC-indexed table lookup during fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry countdown loop predictor trained only by resolved taken\\nbackward conditional branches. When EX sees a taken backedge, record its target\\nand the small instruction-distance from target to branch, then arm a fetch-side\\ndown-counter after redirecting to the loop target. IF decrements the counter\\nonly on real fetch advances; when it expires, it predicts the next PC as the\\nrecorded target without doing any PC tag compare or instruction predecode.\\n\\nCarry predicted-next metadata with each fetched instruction so EX can validate\\nevery prediction against the resolved next PC, redirect on mismatch, and retrain\\nor disable the countdown entry cleanly. This intentionally targets one stable\\ninner-loop backedge and accepts occasional precise mispredictions, trading a\\ntiny counter-zero test and target mux for avoiding the failed predictor logic\\nthat previously lengthened the IF critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add...","metadata":{"matches":18,"truncated":false},"title":"pipeline|stage|fanout|flop|control|forward|hazard|retire|MEM/WB|EX/MEM","time":{"start":1778605221561,"end":1778605221570}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_030e19d6f6d8ccf2016a035ca57070819092658a6ee7d1f2a0"}},"id":"prt_e1d21e6b9001NvqkViJUrkGKa7","sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","messageID":"msg_e1d217b6d001sQ5iUhJ5MIZ16O"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778605221571,"sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_jMn8sNucuFnICt7PY3zEwNAI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (improvement, +41.63%): Moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU mux into an iterative ex_stage div_unit removes rare divide hardware from the FPGA critical path while CoreMark's divide-sparse mix hides the stall latency.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Multi-cycle M-units need a done/ack guard that prevents a held ID/EX M instruction from reasserting start on the ready cycle, or RV32M retirement can lose/corrupt the result in cosim.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +5.13%): IF-stage static branch/JAL predecode can lengthen the imem_data-to-next_pc fetch critical path enough that Fmax loss outweighs CoreMark loop-back bubble savings.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -4.44%): Sharing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU through one sign-controlled 33x33 product can hurt Fmax because operand-signedness muxing and the wider 66-bit multiply cone outweigh removing parallel 32x32 product nets.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -21.07%): A two-entry IF skid queue can cost more than it hides in this shallow CoreMark pipeline, as fetch_pc/valid/pop/full muxing outweighed limited overlap between random imem stalls and backend stalls.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -43.44%): A PC-indexed BTB still puts tag/counter/target lookup plus predicted-next-PC plumbing on the fetch/control path, and in this shallow CoreMark pipeline that cost can swamp warmed-up loop prediction wins.\n7: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (regression, -11.99%): Operand-sensitive load-use predecode plus a MEM-stage store-data bypass can cost more Fmax/control complexity than it saves when CoreMark has too few load-to-store rs2-only bubbles to amortize the extra muxing.\n8: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.50%): A one-entry RAM store buffer still adds sbuf_valid/dmem_ready muxing and ordered-memory stall control on the MEM/hazard path, and CoreMark's random store backpressure was not dominant enough to amortize that backend complexity.\n9: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -38.25%): Even a single-entry tagged redirect predictor leaves a PC tag compare, target mux, and predicted-next-PC metadata on the shallow fetch/EX control path, so shrinking the BTB table alone does not recover enough CoreMark loop bubbles to pay for prediction.\n10: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -4.14%): Moving only MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an iterative ex_stage unit can regress because low-half MUL still keeps the main multiplier cone while added busy/done/result muxing lands on the common EX timing path.\n11: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -49.57%): Return-only RAS prediction still adds imem_data return decode, stack-top next_pc muxing, and predicted-next-PC repair plumbing to the shallow fetch/EX control path, while CoreMark call/return traffic was too sparse to amortize the timing cost.\n12: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.43%): Replacing MEM-stage variable byte-lane shifts with explicit case selectors can regress because synthesis already handles the tiny addr[1:0] shift well, while duplicated load/store mask trees add mux/control pressure on the common load-data and RVFI mask cones.\n13: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -12.44%): Pipelining all MUL variants out of alu.sv into mul_unit still regressed because ex_stage busy/done/result and operand-preservation muxing plus CoreMark MUL stall cycles outweighed removing the product cone from the common ALU path.\n14: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -16.83%): Even a tagless pc[7:2] conditional-backedge predictor leaves a fetch PC compare/target mux plus predicted-next-PC repair plumbing, so CoreMark loop prediction needs a path that avoids adding IF critical-path work.\n15: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (improvement, +6.74%): Stage-specific pipeline control structs improved fitness by dropping EX-only LUI/branch metadata before MEM/WB, showing this shallow FPGA core is fanout/routing-limited enough that pruning dead flops can beat adding control.\n16: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -0.14%): Making the 2R1W write-first register file resetless did not move fitness, suggesting its async read/bypass muxing rather than reset clearing is the relevant FPGA timing/area cost.\n17: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -9.81%): A tagless countdown loop predictor still regressed because counter-zero target muxing plus pred_next_pc metadata and EX-wide prediction_miss repair stayed on common fetch/control paths, outweighing CoreMark backedge bubble savings.\n\n(End of file - total 17 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (improvement, +41.63%): Moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU mux into an iterative ex_stage div_unit removes rare divide hardware from the FPGA critical path while CoreMark's divide-sparse mix hides the stall latency.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Multi-cycle M-units need a done/ack guard that prevents a held ID/EX M instruction from reasserting start on the ready cycle, or RV32M retirement can lose/corrupt the result in cosim.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +5.13%): IF-stage static branch/JAL predecode can lengthen the imem_data-to-next_pc fetch critical path enough that Fmax loss outweighs CoreMark loop-back bubble savings.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512