{"type":"text","timestamp":1778605481255,"sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","part":{"id":"prt_e1d25da5a001GXV35d1jExNpKo","messageID":"msg_e1d221dd2001odzo592HIna5y5","sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","type":"text","text":"Writing the hypothesis as a reset/topology simplification: keep pipeline behavior and RVFI width unchanged, but clear only validity/side-effect control on reset/flush while letting bulk data payload flops become resetless and valid-gated.","time":{"start":1778605480538,"end":1778605481254},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_09c042bd5d0b8158016a035da85db481909b02709210ab4518","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778605506859,"sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_jlynoskVqu8eNY0xCuSm9tkJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Valid-gated resetless pipeline payloads\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\n+\n+  The ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Convert the inter-stage pipeline registers to a valid-gated reset discipline: reset and flush only the valid bits plus control fields that can cause side effects, while leaving bulk data payload flops resetless. Gate redirect, memory request, writeback, forwarding, and RVFI-visible behavior from the existing valid/control discipline so invalid payload data is never architecturally observed.\n+\n+  This is a structural simplification rather than another frontend or memory speculation feature. It should preserve the five-stage single-retire pipeline, nret=1 RVFI contract, CoreMark cycle count, load-use behavior, dmem stall behavior, and RV32IM correctness, while reducing reset fanout, reset mux depth, and routing pressure in the hot pipeline. The expected gain is modest but targets the same class of FPGA costs that made control-struct pruning successful.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change ID/EX reset and flush handling to clear valid and decoded control only, leaving operand, PC, immediate, register-address, and instruction payload flops resetless when they are not valid.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Apply the same valid/control-only reset discipline to EX/MEM, and ensure redirect, divide start, and side-effect control remain gated by a valid input instruction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Make MEM/WB reset clear only valid and side-effect control, while gating dmem requests and misalignment trapping with valid so resetless payload data cannot drive architectural effects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust top-level hazard/RVFI wiring as needed so invalid resetless payloads do not create load-use stalls, forwarding selections, retirements, or nonzero RVFI observations.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"If the existing top-level gating is not sufficient, add explicit valid-aware load-use and stall inputs so resetless invalid control payloads cannot influence pipeline control.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Valid-gated resetless pipeline payloads\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\n+\n+  The ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Convert the inter-stage pipeline registers to a valid-gated reset discipline: reset and flush only the valid bits plus control fields that can cause side effects, while leaving bulk data payload flops resetless. Gate redirect, memory request, writeback, forwarding, and RVFI-visible behavior from the existing valid/control discipline so invalid payload data is never architecturally observed.\n+\n+  This is a structural simplification rather than another frontend or memory speculation feature. It should preserve the five-stage single-retire pipeline, nret=1 RVFI contract, CoreMark cycle count, load-use behavior, dmem stall behavior, and RV32IM correctness, while reducing reset fanout, reset mux depth, and routing pressure in the hot pipeline. The expected gain is modest but targets the same class of FPGA costs that made control-struct pruning successful.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change ID/EX reset and flush handling to clear valid and decoded control only, leaving operand, PC, immediate, register-address, and instruction payload flops resetless when they are not valid.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Apply the same valid/control-only reset discipline to EX/MEM, and ensure redirect, divide start, and side-effect control remain gated by a valid input instruction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Make MEM/WB reset clear only valid and side-effect control, while gating dmem requests and misalignment trapping with valid so resetless payload data cannot drive architectural effects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust top-level hazard/RVFI wiring as needed so invalid resetless payloads do not create load-use stalls, forwarding selections, retirements, or nonzero RVFI observations.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"If the existing top-level gating is not sufficient, add explicit valid-aware load-use and stall inputs so resetless invalid control payloads cannot influence pipeline control.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,25 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\n+title: \"Valid-gated resetless pipeline payloads\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\n+\n+  The ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Convert the inter-stage pipeline registers to a valid-gated reset discipline: reset and flush only the valid bits plus control fields that can cause side effects, while leaving bulk data payload flops resetless. Gate redirect, memory request, writeback, forwarding, and RVFI-visible behavior from the existing valid/control discipline so invalid payload data is never architecturally observed.\n+\n+  This is a structural simplification rather than another frontend or memory speculation feature. It should preserve the five-stage single-retire pipeline, nret=1 RVFI contract, CoreMark cycle count, load-use behavior, dmem stall behavior, and RV32IM correctness, while reducing reset fanout, reset mux depth, and routing pressure in the hot pipeline. The expected gain is modest but targets the same class of FPGA costs that made control-struct pruning successful.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change ID/EX reset and flush handling to clear valid and decoded control only, leaving operand, PC, immediate, register-address, and instruction payload flops resetless when they are not valid.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Apply the same valid/control-only reset discipline to EX/MEM, and ensure redirect, divide start, and side-effect control remain gated by a valid input instruction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Make MEM/WB reset clear only valid and side-effect control, while gating dmem requests and misalignment trapping with valid so resetless payload data cannot drive architectural effects.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust top-level hazard/RVFI wiring as needed so invalid resetless payloads do not create load-use stalls, forwarding selections, retirements, or nonzero RVFI observations.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"If the existing top-level gating is not sufficient, add explicit valid-aware load-use and stall inputs so resetless invalid control payloads cannot influence pipeline control.\"\n","additions":25,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r7s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778605506850,"end":1778605506857}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09c042bd5d0b8158016a035da9293c8190ba3ba716af383d05"}},"id":"prt_e1d25dd27001Y4k00t6q2v0Xgc","sessionID":"ses_1e2de8539ffe926CsZSmkW7oCb","messageID":"msg_e1d221dd2001odzo592HIna5y5"}}
