{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778606916841,"sessionID":"ses_1e2c4ec66ffeomAFIxBSpr6bYE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_NuYtCqEaDNXrS0i5pcXC8cx9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":12,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Split high-half multiplier\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a simple single-cycle low-32-bit product, because that is the\\nmultiply form most likely used by compiled CoreMark matrix code. Move only\\nMULH, MULHU, and MULHSU into a small iterative high-half multiply unit with\\nthe same start/done/ack discipline already proven necessary for the divider.\\n\\nIn the core build, EX should treat the high-half multiply variants like the\\nexisting iterative divider: hold ID/EX while the unit runs, latch the original\\nforwarded operands for RVFI, and emit exactly one EX/MEM res... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 12-12 of 22. Use offset=13 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Split high-half multiplier\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best bench result came from removing cold divide/remainder hardware from\\nthe common execute-stage ALU path, while later attempts that added fetch\\nqueues, predictors, or store buffering lost more Fmax than they recovered in\\ncycles. The remaining ALU still builds signed*signed, unsigned*unsigned, and\\nsigned*unsigned 64-bit multiplier cones even though CoreMark's hot path is\\nexpected to use ordinary low-half MUL far more often than MULH/MULHU/MULHSU.\\n\\nA narrower structural split should preserve CoreMark's common single-cycle\\nmultiply behavior while removing the high-half signedness/product logic from\\nthe timing-critical EX result mux.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a simple single-cycle low-32-bit product, because that is the\\nmultiply form most likely used by compiled CoreMark matrix code. Move only\\nMULH, MULHU, and MULHSU into a small iterative high-half multiply unit with\\nthe same start/done/ack discipline already proven necessary for the divider.\\n\\nIn the core build, EX should treat the high-half multiply variants like the\\nexisting iterative divider: hold ID/EX while the unit runs, latch the original\\nforwarded operands for RVFI, and emit exactly one EX/MEM res... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778606916837,"end":1778606916841}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0086a67bce868276016a036344bf748195a8edd6ed02cb7e6f"}},"id":"prt_e1d3bc4e2001QzkOsp6Imt238c","sessionID":"ses_1e2c4ec66ffeomAFIxBSpr6bYE","messageID":"msg_e1d3b7740001kyJjumnnqUszn2"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778606916904,"sessionID":"ses_1e2c4ec66ffeomAFIxBSpr6bYE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_CVkSBDztiuXOjXQNbxag1lD2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":21,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Valid-gated resetless pipeline payloads\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\\n\\nThe ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\\n\\nThe ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert the inter-stage pipeline registers to a valid-gated reset discipline: reset and flush only the valid bits plus control fields that can cause side effects, while leaving bulk data payload flops resetless. Gate redirect, memory request, writeback, forwarding, and ... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 21-21 of 22. Use offset=22 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Valid-gated resetless pipeline payloads\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline register plumbing rather than by a missing large feature.\\n\\nThe ID/EX, EX/MEM, and MEM/WB registers currently reset entire wide payload structs even though only valid bits and side-effect controls must be deterministic after reset or flush. Resetting every PC, operand, immediate, instruction, RVFI payload, and memory-data field adds high-fanout reset muxing to hundreds of flops without improving steady-state CoreMark IPC.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent structural attempts that added predictors, queues, store buffering, or multi-cycle multiply control regressed because their extra muxing landed on already-sensitive common paths. The strongest recent positive signal was pruning dead pipeline control state, which suggests this core is still limited by fanout/routing and unnecessary pipeline