{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778607268015,"sessionID":"ses_1e2c4ec66ffeomAFIxBSpr6bYE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_KkGZwOO60oY1P1knJ1paeGyV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\n+title: \"MEM-to-EX load bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline pays a one-cycle load-use interlock whenever a load in\n+  EX feeds either raw source field of the following instruction. CoreMark's hot\n+  loops are load-heavy, and the successful recent changes show that this core\n+  is already Fmax-competitive enough that recovering real CPI bubbles may be a\n+  better structural bet than adding more prediction or buffering state.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that added fetch queues, predictors, store buffers,\n+  or multi-cycle multiply control regressed, so this proposal keeps the pipeline\n+  shape and NRET=1 RVFI contract intact while only adding a local load-result\n+  bypass around the existing MEM/EX boundary.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a same-cycle MEM-to-EX forwarding path for loads. When a load is in MEM\n+  and its data is available, feed the MEM-stage sign/zero-extended load result\n+  into the existing EX operand forwarding mux instead of forwarding the load's\n+  address from EX/MEM. Then remove the blanket load-use stall for consumers\n+  that can safely wait under the existing dmem stall mechanism.\n+\n+  Keep correctness conservative for control-flow consumers: if a dependent\n+  branch or JALR would use a load value before the dmem response is valid, hold\n+  it rather than allowing a stale redirect. This should eliminate many common\n+  load-to-ALU, load-to-address, and load-to-store-data bubbles while preserving\n+  precise RVFI source values, trap behavior, and memory ordering.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the current MEM-stage writeback value for loads as a combinational bypass source, using the existing load extension and misalignment gating.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Select the EX/MEM producer for load consumers while allowing core-level wiring to provide load data rather than the load address.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the unconditional load-use interlock with a narrower stall that only holds consumers when the MEM load bypass cannot safely supply the operand.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the load-bypass forwarding value in the existing operand muxes while suppressing dependent redirects until the forwarded load value is valid.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the MEM-stage load bypass data and availability into forwarding, hazard control, and EX redirect safety without changing the top-level NRET=1 IO.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\n+title: \"MEM-to-EX load bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline pays a one-cycle load-use interlock whenever a load in\n+  EX feeds either raw source field of the following instruction. CoreMark's hot\n+  loops are load-heavy, and the successful recent changes show that this core\n+  is already Fmax-competitive enough that recovering real CPI bubbles may be a\n+  better structural bet than adding more prediction or buffering state.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that added fetch queues, predictors, store buffers,\n+  or multi-cycle multiply control regressed, so this proposal keeps the pipeline\n+  shape and NRET=1 RVFI contract intact while only adding a local load-result\n+  bypass around the existing MEM/EX boundary.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a same-cycle MEM-to-EX forwarding path for loads. When a load is in MEM\n+  and its data is available, feed the MEM-stage sign/zero-extended load result\n+  into the existing EX operand forwarding mux instead of forwarding the load's\n+  address from EX/MEM. Then remove the blanket load-use stall for consumers\n+  that can safely wait under the existing dmem stall mechanism.\n+\n+  Keep correctness conservative for control-flow consumers: if a dependent\n+  branch or JALR would use a load value before the dmem response is valid, hold\n+  it rather than allowing a stale redirect. This should eliminate many common\n+  load-to-ALU, load-to-address, and load-to-store-data bubbles while preserving\n+  precise RVFI source values, trap behavior, and memory ordering.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the current MEM-stage writeback value for loads as a combinational bypass source, using the existing load extension and misalignment gating.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Select the EX/MEM producer for load consumers while allowing core-level wiring to provide load data rather than the load address.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the unconditional load-use interlock with a narrower stall that only holds consumers when the MEM load bypass cannot safely supply the operand.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the load-bypass forwarding value in the existing operand muxes while suppressing dependent redirects until the forwarded load value is valid.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the MEM-stage load bypass data and availability into forwarding, hazard control, and EX redirect safety without changing the top-level NRET=1 IO.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,40 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\n+title: \"MEM-to-EX load bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline pays a one-cycle load-use interlock whenever a load in\n+  EX feeds either raw source field of the following instruction. CoreMark's hot\n+  loops are load-heavy, and the successful recent changes show that this core\n+  is already Fmax-competitive enough that recovering real CPI bubbles may be a\n+  better structural bet than adding more prediction or buffering state.\n+\n+  Prior structural attempts that added fetch queues, predictors, store buffers,\n+  or multi-cycle multiply control regressed, so this proposal keeps the pipeline\n+  shape and NRET=1 RVFI contract intact while only adding a local load-result\n+  bypass around the existing MEM/EX boundary.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a same-cycle MEM-to-EX forwarding path for loads. When a load is in MEM\n+  and its data is available, feed the MEM-stage sign/zero-extended load result\n+  into the existing EX operand forwarding mux instead of forwarding the load's\n+  address from EX/MEM. Then remove the blanket load-use stall for consumers\n+  that can safely wait under the existing dmem stall mechanism.\n+\n+  Keep correctness conservative for control-flow consumers: if a dependent\n+  branch or JALR would use a load value before the dmem response is valid, hold\n+  it rather than allowing a stale redirect. This should eliminate many common\n+  load-to-ALU, load-to-address, and load-to-store-data bubbles while preserving\n+  precise RVFI source values, trap behavior, and memory ordering.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose the current MEM-stage writeback value for loads as a combinational bypass source, using the existing load extension and misalignment gating.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Select the EX/MEM producer for load consumers while allowing core-level wiring to provide load data rather than the load address.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the unconditional load-use interlock with a narrower stall that only holds consumers when the MEM load bypass cannot safely supply the operand.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Consume the load-bypass forwarding value in the existing operand muxes while suppressing dependent redirects until the forwarded load value is valid.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the MEM-stage load bypass data and availability into forwarding, hazard control, and EX redirect safety without changing the top-level NRET=1 IO.\"\n","additions":40,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r8s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778607268010,"end":1778607268014}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0682ce21f09eb638016a03648bd8d081949647a037b4d59ee4"}},"id":"prt_e1d40c2b6001of2tHiAt8zfS67","sessionID":"ses_1e2c4ec66ffeomAFIxBSpr6bYE","messageID":"msg_e1d4074e6001xUpWxw7culRPU9"}}
