ld\n24:   it rather than allowing a stale redirect. This should eliminate many common\n25:   load-to-ALU, load-to-address, and load-to-store-data bubbles while preserving\n26:   precise RVFI source values, trap behavior, and memory ordering.\n27: expected_impact:\n28:   fitness_delta_pct: 4\n29:   confidence: medium\n30: changes:\n31:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n32:     description: \"Expose the current MEM-stage writeback value for loads as a combinational bypass source, using the existing load extension and misalignment gating.\"\n33:   - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n34:     description: \"Select the EX/MEM producer for load consumers while allowing core-level wiring to provide load data rather than the load address.\"\n35:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n36:     description: \"Replace the unconditional load-use interlock with a narrower stall that only holds consumers when the MEM load bypass cannot safely supply the operand.\"\n37:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n38:     description: \"Consume the load-bypass forwarding value in the existing operand muxes while suppressing dependent redirects until the forwarded load value is valid.\"\n39:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n40:     description: \"Wire the MEM-stage load bypass data and availability into forwarding, hazard control, and EX redirect safety without changing the top-level NRET=1 IO.\"\n\n(End of file - total 40 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260512-002-r8s1\ntitle: \"MEM-to-EX load bypass\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The current pipeline pays a one-cycle load-use interlock whenever a load in\n  EX feeds either raw source field of the following instruction. CoreMark's hot\n  loops are load-heavy, and the successful recent changes show that this core\n  is already Fmax-competitive enough that recovering real CPI bubbles may be a\n  better structural bet than adding more prediction or buffering state.\n\n  Prior structural attempts that added fetch queues, predictors, store buffers,\n  or 