{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778614269265,"sessionID":"ses_1e2547587ffer0J8SK97dtlKCz","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_NqyTZA0iDyc54B3NNlamyZ8N","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (improvement, +41.63%): Moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU mux into an iterative ex_stage div_unit removes rare divide hardware from the FPGA critical path while CoreMark's divide-sparse mix hides the stall latency.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Multi-cycle M-units need a done/ack guard that prevents a held ID/EX M instruction from reasserting start on the ready cycle, or RV32M retirement can lose/corrupt the result in cosim.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +5.13%): IF-stage static branch/JAL predecode can lengthen the imem_data-to-next_pc fetch critical path enough that Fmax loss outweighs CoreMark loop-back bubble savings.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -4.44%): Sharing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU through one sign-controlled 33x33 product can hurt Fmax because operand-signedness muxing and the wider 66-bit multiply cone outweigh removing parallel 32x32 product nets.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -21.07%): A two-entry IF skid queue can cost more than it hides in this shallow CoreMark pipeline, as fetch_pc/valid/pop/full muxing outweighed limited overlap between random imem stalls and backend stalls.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -43.44%): A PC-indexed BTB still puts tag/counter/target lookup plus predicted-next-PC plumbing on the fetch/control path, and in this shallow CoreMark pipeline that cost can swamp warmed-up loop prediction wins.\n7: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (regression, -11.99%): Operand-sensitive load-use predecode plus a MEM-stage store-data bypass can cost more Fmax/control complexity than it saves when CoreMark has too few load-to-store rs2-only bubbles to amortize the extra muxing.\n8: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.50%): A one-entry RAM store buffer still adds sbuf_valid/dmem_ready muxing and ordered-memory stall control on the MEM/hazard path, and CoreMark's random store backpressure was not dominant enough to amortize that backend complexity.\n9: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -38.25%): Even a single-entry tagged redirect predictor leaves a PC tag compare, target mux, and predicted-next-PC metadata on the shallow fetch/EX control path, so shrinking the BTB table alone does not recover enough CoreMark loop bubbles to pay for prediction.\n10: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -4.14%): Moving only MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an iterative ex_stage unit can regress because low-half MUL still keeps the main multiplier cone while added busy/done/result muxing lands on the common EX timing path.\n11: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -49.57%): Return-only RAS prediction still adds imem_data return decode, stack-top next_pc muxing, and predicted-next-PC repair plumbing to the shallow fetch/EX control path, while CoreMark call/return traffic was too sparse to amortize the timing cost.\n12: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.43%): Replacing MEM-stage variable byte-lane shifts with explicit case selectors can regress because synthesis already handles the tiny addr[1:0] shift well, while duplicated load/store mask trees add mux/control pressure on the common load-data and RVFI mask cones.\n13: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -12.44%): Pipelining all MUL variants out of alu.sv into mul_unit still regressed because ex_stage busy/done/result and operand-preservation muxing plus CoreMark MUL stall cycles outweighed removing the product cone from the common ALU path.\n14: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -16.83%): Even a tagless pc[7:2] conditional-backedge predictor leaves a fetch PC compare/target mux plus predicted-next-PC repair plumbing, so CoreMark loop prediction needs a path that avoids adding IF critical-path work.\n15: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (improvement, +6.74%): Stage-specific pipeline control structs improved fitness by dropping EX-only LUI/branch metadata before MEM/WB, showing this shallow FPGA core is fanout/routing-limited enough that pruning dead flops can beat adding control.\n16: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -0.14%): Making the 2R1W write-first register file resetless did not move fitness, suggesting its async read/bypass muxing rather than reset clearing is the relevant FPGA timing/area cost.\n17: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -9.81%): A tagless countdown loop predictor still regressed because counter-zero target muxing plus pred_next_pc metadata and EX-wide prediction_miss repair stayed on common fetch/control paths, outweighing CoreMark backedge bubble savings.\n18: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (improvement, +1.09%): Resetting only valid/control/hazard fields in pipeline registers trims synchronous reset muxing on wide payload flops, confirming PC/instr/RVFI data can stay don't-care while invalid when side effects are valid-gated.\n19: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (broken, n/a): MEM/WB forwarding cannot be gated by valid-or-current-hold alone because dmem-stall release still needs the invalid-but-held load payload/control for the dependent EX instruction, so resetless payload cleanup must preserve that bypass contract.\n20: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -18.42%): Decode-stage direct-JAL prediction still adds decoder/imm_gen/target-add feedback into the IF PC mux, and CoreMark's direct-JAL bubble savings were too small to offset that new control-path timing cost.\n21: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r8s0 (regression, -3.83%): Removing duplicate EX/MEM store-data payload can regress when the extra register was isolating rs2_val fanout between MEM byte-replication/store paths and RVFI source reporting.\n22: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r8s1 (regression, -10.76%): Same-cycle MEM-to-EX load bypass puts dmem read-data extension and ready/forward gating on the EX operand/redirect path, so its timing cost can outweigh CoreMark load-use bubble savings.\n23: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r8s2 (regression, -22.31%): Registering a one-entry backedge predictor avoids same-cycle tag lookup but still adds pred_valid/target PC muxing plus EX miss/clear/train plumbing, so predictor repair metadata alone can outweigh CoreMark loop-bubble savings.\n24: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r9s0 (regression, -4.46%): Explicitly sharing EX pc_plus4/pc_imm_sum/JALR target and branch comparator primitives can regress because synthesis already optimizes these simple cones, while the named shared nets increase fanout across redirect, link, pc_next, and RVFI paths.\n25: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r9s1 (regression, -10.21%): Registering a single MEM/WB wb_data value can regress because it moves the load-vs-ALU mux onto the MEM/load-data capture path while removing a late WB mux that synthesis already handled cheaply.\n26: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r9s2 (regression, -22.23%): Redirect-target instruction replay avoided normal pc+4 prediction work but still regressed because replay-hit compares, target+4 PC muxing, and flush suppression moved complexity onto the redirect/hazard path where CoreMark bubble savings could not amortize it.\n27: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r10s0 (regression, +4.63%): Splitting rvfi_order into lo/hi counters can regress because FPGA synthesis already maps a 64-bit incrementer efficiently, while the explicit low-wrap compare and high-half enable add control/routing overhead on retirement logic.\n28: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r10s1 (regression, -26.19%): Removing regfile write-first muxes by adding a captured previous-WB forwarding source can regress because the extra EX operand select path and ID/EX-held bypass state cost more than the rare same-cycle WB/read repair they replace.\n29: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r10s2 (improvement, +21.48%): An IF replay table trained only on accepted fetches can turn CoreMark's random hot-loop imem stalls into useful instructions via imem_effective_ready without paying the target-lookup and EX-repair metadata costs that sank branch predictors.\n30: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r11s0 (regression, -8.82%): Making IF replay tag/instr payload arrays resetless regressed despite valid gating, so the replay table's binding cost is likely compare/control routing rather than reset mux fanout on its small payload flops.\n31: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r11s1 (regression, -5.04%): Widening the direct-mapped IF replay table from 8 to 16 entries regressed, suggesting CoreMark replay is not capacity-limited enough to pay for extra index/tag/valid routing on the fetch path.\n32: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r12s0 (regression, +0.00%): Shrinking IF replay tags from pc[31:5] to pc[19:5] did not move fitness, implying the accepted-fetch replay table is limited by ready/hit control and fetch mux routing rather than raw tag flop/comparator width.\n33: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r12s1 (regression, -57.52%): Opportunistic IF replay warming during backend stalls regressed because decoupling io_imemAddr from pc adds imem_addr_q==pc qualification, warm-cursor updates, and replay-fill muxing on the fetch ready/hit path that extra training could not amortize.\n34: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r12s2 (regression, -19.56%): Line-packed IF replay regressed because half-select valid/data muxing and wider line-tag update control add fetch-ready path complexity that outweighed reducing the number of stored tags.\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (improvement, +41.63%): Moving DIV/REM out of the combinational ALU mux into an iterative ex_stage div_unit removes rare divide hardware from the FPGA critical path while CoreMark's divide-sparse mix hides the stall latency.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (broken, n/a): Multi-cycle M-units need a done/ack guard that prevents a held ID/EX M instruction from reasserting start on the ready cycle, or RV32M retirement can lose/corrupt the result in cosim.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +5.13%): IF-stage static branch/JAL predecode can lengthen the imem_data-to-next_pc fetch critical path enough that Fmax loss outweighs CoreMark loop-back bubble savings.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -4.44%): Sharing MUL/MULH/MULHU/MULHSU through one sign-controlled 33x33 product can hurt Fmax because operand-signedness muxing and the wider 66-bit multiply cone outweigh removing parallel 32x32 product nets.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -21.07%): A two-entry IF skid queue can cost more than it hides in this shallow CoreMark pipeline, as fetch_pc/valid/pop/full muxing outweighed limited overlap between random imem stalls and backend stalls.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -43.44%): A PC-indexed BTB still puts tag/counter/target lookup plus predicted-next-PC plumbing on the fetch/control path, and in this shallow CoreMark pipeline that cost can swamp warmed-up loop prediction wins.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r3s0 (regression, -11.99%): Operand-sensitive load-use predecode plus a MEM-stage store-data bypass can cost more Fmax/control complexity than it saves when CoreMark has too few load-to-store rs2-only bubbles to amortize the extra muxing.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.50%): A one-entry RAM store buffer still adds sbuf_valid/dmem_ready muxing and ordered-memory stall control on the MEM/hazard path, and CoreMark's random store backpressure was not dominant enough to amortize that backend complexity.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r3s2 (regression, -38.25%): Even a single-entry tagged redirect predictor leaves a PC tag compare, target mux, and predicted-next-PC metadata on the shallow fetch/EX control path, so shrinking the BTB table alone does not recover enough CoreMark loop bubbles to pay for prediction.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r4s0 (regression, -4.14%): Moving only MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an iterative ex_stage unit can regress because low-half MUL still keeps the main multiplier cone while added busy/done/result muxing lands on the common EX timing path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r4s2 (regression, -49.57%): Return-only RAS prediction still adds imem_data return decode, stack-top next_pc muxing, and predicted-next-PC repair plumbing to the shallow fetch/EX control path, while CoreMark call/return traffic was too sparse to amortize the timing cost.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r5s0 (regression, -5.43%): Replacing MEM-stage variable byte-lane shifts with explicit case selectors can regress because synthesis already handles the tiny addr[1:0] shift well, while duplicated load/store mask trees add mux/control pressure on the common load-data and RVFI mask cones.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r5s1 (regression, -12.44%): Pipelining all MUL variants out of alu.sv into mul_unit still regressed because ex_stage busy/done/result and operand-preservation muxing plus CoreMark MUL stall cycles outweighed removing the product cone from the common ALU path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r5s2 (regression, -16.83%): Even a tagless pc[7:2] conditional-backedge predictor leaves a fetch PC compare/target mux plus predicted-next-PC repair plumbing, so CoreMark loop prediction needs a path that avoids adding IF critical-path work.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r6s0 (improvement, +6.74%): Stage-specific pipeline control structs improved fitness by dropping EX-only LUI/branch metadata before MEM/WB, showing this shallow FPGA core is fanout/routing-limited enough that pruning dead flops can beat adding control.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r6s1 (regression, -0.14%): Making the 2R1W write-first register file resetless did not move fitness, suggesting its async read/bypass muxing rather than reset clearing is the relevant FPGA timing/area cost.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r6s2 (regression, -9.81%): A tagless countdown loop predictor still regressed because counter-zero target muxing plus pred_next_pc metadata and EX-wide prediction_miss repair stayed on common fetch/control paths, outweighing CoreMark backedge bubble savings.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r7s0 (improvement, +1.09%): Resetting only valid/control/hazard fields in pipeline registers trims synchronous reset muxing on wide payload flops, confirming PC/instr/RVFI data can stay don't-care while invalid when side effects are valid-gated.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r7s1 (broken, n/a): MEM/WB forwarding cannot be gated by valid-or-current-hold alone because dmem-stall release still needs the invalid-but-held load payload/control for the dependent EX instruction, so resetless payload cleanup must preserve that bypass contract.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r7s2 (regression, -18.42%): Decode-stage direct-JAL prediction still adds decoder/imm_gen/target-add feedback into the IF PC mux, and CoreMark's direct-JAL bubble savings were too small to offset that new control-path timing cost.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778614269259,"end":1778614269264}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0928efe84f5c9545016a037ffd11d88193b434f7e35b418c48"}},"id":"prt_e1dabf548001Ks859Rq6OPblhB","sessionID":"ses_1e2547587ffer0J8SK97dtlKCz","messageID":"msg_e1dab8b30001DZNv7KjvlXMJFM"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778614269496,"sessionID":"ses_1e2547587ffer0J8SK97dtlKCz","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_PdrGLBo6aZQxoUSsKCdlqAFp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"predictor|BTB|branch|JAL|RAS|replay|backedge|countdown|redirect","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 33 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Iterative divider off ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current ALU implements RV32IM DIV/REM with combinational / and % operators\\nin the same execute-stage result mux as the common integer and multiply ops.\\nCoreMark is dominated by adds, branches, loads, stores, and multiplies; rare\\ndivision hardware can still cap FPGA Fmax and consume LUTs even when it is not\\non the dynamic hot path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace only DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU with a small iterative divider/rem unit and\\nstall the single-issue pipeline while that unit is busy. Keep ADD/SUB/logic,\\nshifts, compares, address generation, branches, jumps, and all MUL/MULH\\nvariants single-cycle. This trades latency on rare divide instructions for a\\nshorter EX-stage combinational path and lower LUT pressure, which should raise\\nmedian Tang Nano 20K Fmax without materially changing CoreMark cycles.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real combinational DIV/REM/% paths from the ALU while preserving ALTOPS behavior and single-cycle non-divide operations.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/div_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a sequential RV32M-correct divider/remainder unit covering signed, unsigned, divide-by-zero, and INT_MIN/-1 semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Start the divider for DIV/REM ops, hold the instruction until completion, and latch the final quotient or remainder into EX/MEM.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an execute-busy stall input so IF...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Decouple RV32M from EX critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current EX stage contains the full RV32IM ALU, including three 64-bit multiply products and combinational divide/remainder logic. Even when CoreMark is executing ordinary RV32I ALU, branch, and memory instructions, that wide M-extension datapath remains part of the synthesized execute-stage cone and likely limits Fmax near the Tang Nano 20K LUT budget.\\n\\nA structural split that keeps common RV32I operations single-cycle while moving RV32M work into a dedicated busy/ready unit should raise Fmax and reduce routing pressure. CoreMark uses multiply but rarely needs divide in the timed loop, so a modest multiply latency penalty should be outweighed by a shorter critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a separate M-unit and make EX a one-cycle stage for RV32I plus a multi-cycle/busy stage only for ALU_MUL*, ALU_DIV*, and ALU_REM*. Implement multiply as a short pipelined DSP-friendly path and division/remainder as an iterative unit, with the hazard unit freezing IF/ID/EX while an M operation is outstanding and releasing exactly one EX/MEM result when ready.\\n\\nUnder RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS, keep the M-unit's substituted algebraic results one-cycle or...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static IF backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX and redirects on every taken control transfer. CoreMark spends much of its timed region in tight loops, so backward loop branches repeatedly pay a wrong-path bubble even though their target is statically knowable from the fetched instruction. A small static predictor can recover those bubbles while preserving the single-issue RVFI contract and avoiding a large Fmax hit.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add IF-stage predecode for conditional branches and JAL. Predict JAL as taken, predict conditional branches as taken only when the B-immediate is negative, and otherwise predict fall-through