predictor and does not carry prediction metadata\\ninto EX. It attacks repeated hot-loop iStalls while avoiding the failed IF\\nbranch-predecode/BTB/RAS/backedge-repair paths. Because the instruction memory\\nis immutable in FPGA/cosim and formal ties io_imemReady high, a replay hit is\\narchitecturally the same instruction word previously observed for that PC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an 8-entry PC-tagged instruction replay predictor, fill it on accepted ready fetches,... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n32: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Resetless IF replay payloads\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the accepted-fetch-only replay behavior exactly as-is, but reset only the\\nreplay_valid bits. Leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload registers\\nresetless because they are architecturally ignored whenever their valid bit is\\nclear and fully overwritten before any replay hit can occur.\\n\\nThis should trim synchronous reset muxing and reset-tree fanout introduced by\\nthe replay predictor without adding new prediction metadata, bypassing, or PC\\nmuxing. IPC should remain unchanged, while median Tang Nano 20K Fmax may rise\\nmodestly from lower IF-stage routing pressure.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Reset only replay_valid and the PC; leave replay_tag and replay_instr payload arrays resetless while preserving fill-on-imem-ready and replay-hit gating.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_de... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n33: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r11s1\", \"title\": \"Wider resetless ifetch replay cache\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The latest winning change showed that the safest remaining cycle gain is not\\nbranch prediction, but replaying immutable hot-loop instructions when the\\nrandom instruction bus stalls. The current replay table is only 8 entries and\\ndirect-mapped, so CoreMark loop bodies can still conflict on pc[4:2] and fall\\nback to bubbles even after the instruction was previously fetched.\\n\\nPrior structural attempts that added queues, store buffers, bypass paths, or\\npredictor metadata regressed because they lengthened common control paths.\\nA larger direct-mapped replay cache keeps the same no-repair frontend shape\\nwhile improving the hit rate of the one mechanism that has already produced a\\nlarge fitness win.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Rebuild the IF replay table as a 16-entry direct-mapped, valid-gated replay\\ncache indexed by pc[5:2]. Fill it only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, and\\non io_imemReady=0 hits keep supplying the cached instruction through the\\nexisting imem_effective_ready path. Do not add branch prediction metadata,\\ntarget repair state, or any EX feedback.\\n\\nMake the replay tag and instruction payload arrays reset... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n34: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r11s2\", \"title\": \"Wider ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only successful predictor result so far was the tiny instruction-fetch\\nreplay table, because it converts random hot-loop instruction-bus stalls into\\nuseful decode cycles without adding branch target lookup, prediction repair,\\nor EX-stage metadata. CoreMark's timed working set is larger than eight\\nfetch-table slots, so direct-mapped conflicts can still turn repeated PCs\\nback into imem stalls even after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only successful predictor result so far was the tiny instruction-fetch\\nreplay table, because it converts random hot-loop instruction-bus stalls into\\nuseful decode cycles without adding branch target lookup, prediction repair,\\nor EX-stage metadata. CoreMark's timed working set is larger than eight\\nfetch-table slots, so direct-mapped conflicts can still turn repeated PCs\\nback into imem stalls even after warmup.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the IF-stage instruction replay predictor from 8 direct-mapped entries\\nto 16 direct-mapped entries while keeping the exact same training and use\\ndiscipline: fill only on accepted io_imemReady fetches, replay only when\\nio_imemReady is low and the current PC tag hits, and leave all branch/jump\\nprediction behavior unchanged. This should reduce replay conflict misses in\\nCoreMark hot loops under the 22% random iStall model while avoiding the\\ntarget-PC muxing and prediction-repair metadata that made earlier branch\\npredictors regress. The added hardware is one more index bit and a modestly\\nlarger tag/instruction array, so the expected gain is smaller than the first\\nreplay predictor but still plausible.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Increase the PC-tagged instruction replay predictor to 16 direct-mapped entries, preserving fill-on-ready and replay-on-stall semantics.\"}... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n35: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r12s0\", \"title\": \"Trim IF replay tags to memory range\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The 8-entry IF replay table is the current strongest cycle-side win, but the\\nfollow-up attempts show the table is sensitive to routing: resetless payloads\\nand wider tables regressed, and the lesson points at compare/control cost\\nrather than capacity. Each replay entry still stores and compares pc[31:5],\\neven though valid instruction fetches for this benchmark contract are bounded\\nto the 1 MiB memory window.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The 8-entry IF replay table is the current strongest cycle-side win, but the\\nfollow-up attempts show the table is sensitive to routing: resetless payloads\\nand wider tables regressed, and the lesson points at compare/control cost\\nrather than capacity. Each replay entry still stores and compares pc[31:5],\\neven though valid instruction fetches for this benchmark contract are bounded\\nto the 1 MiB memory window.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the accepted-fetch-only 8-entry replay table and its exact ready/hit\\nsemantics, but shrink replay_tag from pc[31:5] to pc[19:5]. Together with the\\nexisting pc[4:2] index, those bits uniquely identify every word-aligned fetch\\naddress in the legal [0x00000000, 0x00100000) instruction-memory region, so\\nCoreMark hit behavior and correctness for in-bounds execution are unchanged.\\n\\nThis removes 96 replay-tag flops and cuts each replay-hit comparator from 27\\nbits to 15 bits, directly attacking the IF-stage compare/routing pressure that\\nlikely limited the replay-table follow-ups. Formal keeps imemReady high, and\\nout-of-range PCs already violate the memory-bounds invariant rather than\\nrelying on replay tags for recovery.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Store and compare only replay_tag=pc[19:5] while preserving the 8-entry pc[4:2] index, fill-on-ready behavior, replay-on-stall h... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n36: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r12s1\", \"title\": \"Warm replay during backend stalls\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current 8-entry IF replay table produced the largest recent improvement by\\nconverting random instruction-bus stalls into useful hot-loop instructions.\\nFollow-up attempts to widen or reset-retime the table regressed, which points\\naway from adding capacity on the fetch critical path and toward improving how\\noften the existing table is populated.\\n\\nBackend stalls from dmem backpressure, load-use bubbles, and iterative divide\\nalready stop decode from consuming the current fetch slot. Those cycles can be\\nused to issue harmless sequential instruction fetches and train the replay\\ntable, because instruction memory is immutable and wrong-path replay fills do\\nnot affect architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current 8-entry IF replay table produced the largest recent improvement by\\nconverting random instruction-bus stalls into useful hot-loop instructions.\\nFollow-up attempts to widen or reset-retime the table regressed, which points\\naway from adding capacity on the fetch critical path and toward improving how\\noften the existing table is populated.\\n\\nBackend stalls from dmem backpressure, load-use bubbles, and iterative divide\\nalready stop decode from consuming the current fetch slot. Those cycles can be\\nused to issue harmless sequential instruction fetches and train the replay\\ntable, because instruction memory is immutable and wrong-path replay fills do\\nnot affect architectural state.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add an opportunistic replay warmer inside IF. When the architectural PC is\\nheld for a non-redirect backend stall and the instruction bus is ready, drive\\nio_imemAddr from a small sequential prefetch cursor instead of the held PC and\\nfill the existing replay table with the returned instruction. Keep out.pc,\\nRVFI-visible instruction flow, redirect handling, and decode consumption tied\\nto the architectural PC; the wa... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n37: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r12s2\", \"title\": \"Line-packed ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The only predictor that improved this bench core was the tiny instruction-fetch replay table, which converts random hot-loop iStall cycles into useful decoded instructions without branch target prediction or EX repair metadata. Follow-up attempts to widen the table or remove payload resets regressed, suggesting the remaining replay cost is tag/control routing rather than capacity or reset muxing.\\n\\nA predictor refinement should therefore keep the accepted-fetch-only replay semantics but reduce the fetch-stage compare and tag storage pressure that now sits on every stalled fetch decision.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The only predictor that improved this bench core was the tiny instruction-fetch replay table, which converts random hot-loop iStall cycles into useful decoded instructions without branch target prediction or EX repair metadata. Follow-up attempts to widen the table or remove payload resets regressed, suggesting the remaining replay cost is tag/control routing rather than capacity or reset muxing.\\n\\nA predictor refinement should therefore keep the accepted-fetch-only replay semantics but reduce the fetch-stage compare and tag storage pressure that now sits on every stalled fetch decision.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Repack the current 8-entry single-word replay table into four two-word replay lines. Each line stores one full PC tag, two instruction words, and per-word valid bits; accepted fetches fill only the addressed half, clearing the sibling valid bit when a different tag replaces the line. On io_imemReady=0, a replay hit still requires a full tag match plus the selected half valid bit, then supplies the cached immutable instruction and asserts imem_effective_ready exactly as today.\\n\\nThis preserves the successful no-branch-prediction replay model and the NRET=1 RVFI contract while halving the number of stored tags and tag-select ro... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 37 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny ifetch replay predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictors for this core consistently regressed because they put\\ntarget lookup, instruction predecode, prediction metadata, or repair muxing on\\nthe shallow fetch/redirect path. The apples-to-apples CoreMark mode also has\\nroughly 22% random instruction-bus stalls, and the current frontend turns every\\nlow io_imemReady cycle into a NOP even when the same hot-loop PC was fetched\\ncorrectly on an earlier iteration.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny direct-mapped instruction replay predictor trained only by accepted\\ninstruction fetches. On an io_imemReady=1 fetch, record {PC tag, instruction}\\nin an 8-entry table. On a later io_imemReady=0 cycle, if the current PC hits\\nthe table, supply the cached instruction and treat fetch as effectively ready;\\notherwise keep the existing stall/NOP behavior.\\n\\nThis is not a branch target predictor and does not carry prediction metadata\\ninto EX. It attacks repeated hot-loop iStalls while avoiding the failed IF\\nbranch-predecode/BTB/RAS/backedge-repair paths. Because the instruction memory\\nis immutable in FPGA/cosim and formal ties io_imemReady high, a replay hit is\\narchitecturally the same instruction word previously observed for that PC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an 8-entry PC-tagged instruction replay predictor, fill it on accepted ready fetches,... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r11s0\", \"title\": \"Resetless IF replay payloads\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The latest winning change added an 8-entry instruction replay table in IF,\\nwhich improved CoreMark cycles under random instruction stalls but also added\\nhundreds of resettable tag/instruction payload flops to a stage that is already\\nsensitive to routing and control fanout. Earlier micro-opt wins came from\\npruning dead control and unnecessary reset muxing, and the replay table only\\nneeds deterministic validity after reset, not deterministic payload contents.\\n\", \"hypothes