{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778598664504,"sessionID":"ses_1e3449677ffecMtIiQMoiKFNUT","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_CNHfhWxytpybgiqqGPMgAQDD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\n+title: \"One-entry hot redirect predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The previous predictor attempts show that CoreMark has exploitable taken loop\n+  control flow, but larger or instruction-predecode-based predictors hurt the\n+  Tang Nano 20K fetch critical path enough to erase the cycle savings. The most\n+  promising remaining predictor angle is to keep the frontend prediction logic\n+  deliberately tiny and only target the hottest repeated redirect.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry tagged redirect cache in IF. On an exact fetch-PC tag hit,\n+  predict the cached target as the next PC; otherwise fetch pc+4. EX carries the\n+  predicted-next metadata, resolves the actual next PC for every retiring\n+  instruction, redirects only on a prediction mismatch, updates the entry on\n+  taken branches and jumps, and invalidates it when the same PC resolves not\n+  taken or non-control.\n+\n+  This recovers steady-state bubbles for one dominant CoreMark loop backedge or\n+  repeated jump while avoiding the failed imem_data predecode path and avoiding\n+  a multi-entry BTB/BHT table. The hardware cost should be one valid bit, one\n+  PC tag compare, one target register, and a next-PC mux, so the Fmax risk is\n+  much lower than the prior predictor designs.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted-next-PC and predicted-taken metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate the one-entry prediction precisely.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add the one-entry tagged redirect cache, PC-hit prediction mux, and EX update/invalidate interface without decoding io_imemData in the fetch path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Latch the IF prediction metadata into ID/EX alongside the existing instruction, PC, operands, and control fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Resolve actual next PC for all instructions, redirect only on prediction mismatch, and emit update/invalidate signals for the hot redirect cache.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the predictor metadata and update signals between IF, ID, and EX while preserving the existing NRET=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,36 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r3s2\n+title: \"One-entry hot redirect predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The previous predictor attempts show that CoreMark has exploitable taken loop\n+  control flow, but larger or instruction-predecode-based predictors hurt the\n+  Tang Nano 20K fetch critical path enough to erase the cycle savings. The most\n+  promising remaining predictor angle is to keep the frontend prediction logic\n+  deliberately tiny and only target the hottest repeated redirect.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry tagged redirect cache in IF. On an exact fetch-PC tag hit,\n+  predict the cached target as the next PC; otherwise fetch pc+4. EX carries the\n+  predicted-next metadata, resolves the actual next PC for every retiring\n+  instruction, redirects only on a prediction mismatch, updates the entry on\n+  taken branches and jumps, and invalidates it when the same PC resolves not\n+  taken or non-control.\n+\n+  This recovers steady-state bubbles for one dominant CoreMark loop backedge or\n+  repeated jump while avoiding the failed imem_data predecode path and avoiding\n+  a multi-entry BTB/BHT table. The hardware cost should be one valid bit, one\n+  PC tag compare, one target register, and a next-PC mux, so the Fmax risk is\n+  much lower than the prior predictor designs.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted-next-PC and predicted-taken metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate the one-entry prediction precisely.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add the one-entry tagged redirect cache, PC-hit prediction mux, and EX update/invalidate interface without decoding io_imemData in the fetch path.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Latch the IF prediction metadata into ID/EX alongside the existing instruction, PC, operands, and control fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Resolve actual next PC for all instructions, redirect only on prediction mismatch, and emit update/invalidate signals for the hot redirect cache.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the predictor metadata and update signals between IF, ID, and EX while preserving the existing NRET=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r3s2.yaml","type":"add","p