{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1778600404585,"sessionID":"ses_1e327f8ecffeMPojppYvchHBN1","part":{"id":"prt_e1cd86667001T65lxJ8OvTd68X","messageID":"msg_e1cd86246001eHQyNuvZrdEkr9","sessionID":"ses_1e327f8ecffeMPojppYvchHBN1","snapshot":"bcfca979fe152382da3916e267fd68fb4357bbee","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778600512556,"sessionID":"ses_1e327f8ecffeMPojppYvchHBN1","part":{"id":"prt_e1cda057e0013R7nLU8KVQsSEL","messageID":"msg_e1cd86246001eHQyNuvZrdEkr9","sessionID":"ses_1e327f8ecffeMPojppYvchHBN1","type":"text","text":"Prior predictor attempts all paid for fetch-side target generation or tag/target lookup. I’m writing a narrower return-address-stack hypothesis that targets JALR returns with a tiny opcode/register predecode and no BTB table or branch immediate adder in the IF next-PC path.","time":{"start":1778600510846,"end":1778600512555},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_02919764f79166cd016a034a3eb82c8190aaeb1794856f56d4","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778600535144,"sessionID":"ses_1e327f8ecffeMPojppYvchHBN1","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_ww9bsIztbloMzaeVSSWOXCGO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Return-address stack predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts on this core regressed because they put too much\n+  target-generation or tag-lookup logic on the shallow fetch critical path.\n+  CoreMark still contains repeated call/return control flow in addition to\n+  loops, and returns are the one dynamic-control case where a tiny predictor\n+  can provide a target without a BTB target array or branch-immediate adder.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a small return-address stack for JALR return prediction only. Push\n+  pc+4 when a legal link-register JAL/JALR call resolves, pop when a legal\n+  return resolves, and in IF predict a fetched `jalr x0, x1/x5, 0` to the\n+  current stack top. Carry predicted-next-PC metadata to EX so a correctly\n+  predicted return does not flush, while any mismatch redirects and repairs\n+  the stack precisely.\n+\n+  This intentionally does not predict conditional branches and does not add\n+  a PC-indexed BTB/tag compare. The IF critical-path addition should be only\n+  a narrow opcode/rd/rs1/imm-zero return recognizer plus a mux to the stack\n+  top, so Fmax risk is lower than the failed static branch, BTB, and hot\n+  redirect predictor variants. The cycle gain is expected to be modest but\n+  positive if CoreMark's timed call/return traffic is frequent enough.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted-next-PC and return-predicted metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles for precise EX validation.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Implement a tiny RAS and predict only canonical return JALR instructions to the stack top, with EX repair/update inputs.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Carry the return prediction metadata through the ID/EX register without changing decode legality rules.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Classify resolved calls and returns, compare actual next PC against the carried prediction, and emit RAS push/pop/repair updates.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire prediction validation and RAS update signals between IF and EX while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r4s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,37 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Return-address stack predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts on this core regressed because they put too much\n+  target-generation or tag-lookup logic on the shallow fetch critical path.\n+  CoreMark still contains repeated call/return control flow in addition to\n+  loops, and returns are the one dynamic-control case where a tiny predictor\n+  can provide a target without a BTB target array or branch-immediate adder.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a small return-address stack for JALR return prediction only. Push\n+  pc+4 when a legal link-register JAL/JALR call resolves, pop when a legal\n+  return resolves, and in IF pre