{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778608990364,"sessionID":"ses_1e2a7c356ffeKwI3WRIPgNGjbR","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_JKvG9EH0fPsa6f9bR1lFiJyI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r9s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r9s2\n+title: \"Redirect target replay predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts found real CoreMark loop-control opportunity, but every design that changed the normal fetch next-PC path with predecode, PC compares, target muxes, or prediction metadata lost more Fmax than it recovered in CPI. The remaining predictor angle should avoid making every sequential fetch pay for loop prediction.\n+\n+  A tiny target-instruction replay buffer can target the same repeated taken backedges without predicting the PC ahead of time. It only acts on an actual EX redirect and tries to fill the redirect bubble with a previously observed target instruction, so the common pc+4 fetch path stays essentially unchanged.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry redirect-target replay predictor inside IF. When a taken branch or jump redirects to a target and the target instruction is fetched normally, record the target PC and instruction word. On a later EX redirect to the same target, emit the cached target instruction and target PC into ID during the redirect cycle instead of forcing a NOP, while still updating the real PC to the redirect target.\n+\n+  This should recover one bubble for hot loop backedges after warmup without a BTB lookup, current-PC tag compare, imem_data branch predecode, or predicted-next-PC metadata on normal fetch cycles. Mismatches are not speculative branch predictions: the buffer is only used after EX has already resolved a redirect, and it should be disabled whenever the pipeline is held by dmem/ex_busy or the target entry is not valid. Program memory is immutable for the benchmark, so replaying the cached instruction for the same target PC preserves RVFI instruction/PC behavior.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry redirect-target instruction replay buffer, fill it after normal target fetches, and on an EX redirect hit emit the cached target IF/ID payload instead of a NOP while leaving the normal pc+4 path unchanged.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Add a redirect-replay hit input so redirect flushes still kill wrong-path state on misses, but allow ID/EX to capture the replayed target instruction when the buffer supplies a valid redirect-cycle payload.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the IF replay-hit signal into hazard control and pass any needed ready/hold context to IF without changing the NRET=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r9s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r9s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r9s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_xhigh-rep2/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-003-r9s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-003-r9s2\n+title: \"Redirect target replay predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior predictor attempts found real CoreMark loop-control opportunity, but every design that changed the normal fetch next-PC path with predecode, PC compares, target muxes, or prediction metadata lost more Fmax than it recovered in CPI. The remaining predictor angle should avoid making every sequential fet